00:02:26.980 --> 00:02:29.975
The conversion efficiency is the
output energy versus the input.

00:02:29.975 --> 00:02:32.600
We have our inputs in the solar
spectrum, the outputs in charge

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:34.820
collection, and we've been
steadily making progress

00:02:34.820 --> 00:02:37.020
down toward the outputs here.

00:02:37.020 --> 00:02:38.580
We discussed the
solar spectrum, then

00:02:38.580 --> 00:02:40.270
light absorption, the
charge excitation,

00:02:40.270 --> 00:02:45.330
and finally now we're on to
charge drift and diffusion.

00:02:45.330 --> 00:02:49.310
So we have the total
solar cell efficiency

00:02:49.310 --> 00:02:51.390
as a product of all the
individual processes.

00:02:51.390 --> 00:02:53.480
And any one of these
processes can kill

00:02:53.480 --> 00:02:54.784
the efficiency of the device.

00:02:54.784 --> 00:02:56.950
That's why it's important
to think about your device

00:02:56.950 --> 00:02:57.970
like so.

00:02:57.970 --> 00:03:00.530
And just not to make this
introduction so boring,

00:03:00.530 --> 00:03:02.190
I want to really
emphasize this point.

00:03:02.190 --> 00:03:04.090
So I'm making it
over and over again.

00:03:04.090 --> 00:03:07.530
But I wanted to relate this
to other engineering devices

00:03:07.530 --> 00:03:08.440
as well.

00:03:08.440 --> 00:03:10.730
Namely, today it's
a Toyota Prius.

00:03:10.730 --> 00:03:12.770
These are all the
components inside of a Prius

00:03:12.770 --> 00:03:15.870
that have to work well
for the car to function.

00:03:15.870 --> 00:03:18.320
If one of these
components, let's say

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:22.750
this one, the inverter, is
broken or not functioning well,

00:03:22.750 --> 00:03:26.240
you're not going to have the
car in an autonomous mode.

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:28.100
So in a similar
manner, in a solar cell

00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:30.100
we have to have all the
different pieces working

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:32.490
well together.

00:03:32.490 --> 00:03:34.180
So the essence of
charge separation,

00:03:34.180 --> 00:03:36.920
we're going to begin our
exploration of charge

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:40.210
separation using
the diode analogy.

00:03:40.210 --> 00:03:43.170
And just to situate
everybody, I brought

00:03:43.170 --> 00:03:47.090
in a number of small discrete
components, small diodes.

00:03:47.090 --> 00:03:49.890
Those are the ones
that are orange-ish

00:03:49.890 --> 00:03:51.460
that have two leads coming out.

00:03:51.460 --> 00:03:53.030
There are a bunch of
transistors in here as well.

00:03:53.030 --> 00:03:54.739
Those have three little
leads coming out.

00:03:54.739 --> 00:03:56.196
You'll be able to
distinguish them.

00:03:56.196 --> 00:03:58.320
But just to situate
ourselves, these are diodes.

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:02.660
The essence of a diode is that
you have a dissimilar material

00:04:02.660 --> 00:04:05.340
on either side of the device.

00:04:05.340 --> 00:04:07.510
That's why I've worn these
dissimilar colors today

00:04:07.510 --> 00:04:09.927
to denote that on
different sides.

00:04:09.927 --> 00:04:12.260
And of course, you have this
mixed region in the middle.

00:04:12.260 --> 00:04:15.680
We have here an n and
a p on either side.

00:04:15.680 --> 00:04:18.040
And if current is attempting
to flow in one direction,

00:04:18.040 --> 00:04:18.640
it will be barred.

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:20.723
But if it attempts to flow
in the other direction,

00:04:20.723 --> 00:04:22.360
it will go through
rather easily.

00:04:22.360 --> 00:04:25.240
That's the essence
of what a diode is.

00:04:25.240 --> 00:04:26.640
How is it made?

00:04:26.640 --> 00:04:29.150
Well, we're
manufacturing materials

00:04:29.150 --> 00:04:31.660
of the same base element.

00:04:31.660 --> 00:04:32.930
Let's say, silicon.

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:34.630
But we're doing
something special

00:04:34.630 --> 00:04:37.650
to the material to add
particular types of charges

00:04:37.650 --> 00:04:38.300
on either side.

00:04:38.300 --> 00:04:39.150
We call doping.

00:04:39.150 --> 00:04:41.210
And we'll get to
that in a few slides.

00:04:41.210 --> 00:04:42.430
Why do we care about diodes?

00:04:42.430 --> 00:04:45.520
Well, this is the essence
of charge separation.

00:04:45.520 --> 00:04:48.160
And this is what drives the
voltage inside of a solar cell

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:48.660
device.

00:04:48.660 --> 00:04:49.750
That's why we care.

00:04:49.750 --> 00:04:52.170
It's pretty important for
at least understanding

00:04:52.170 --> 00:04:55.810
the traditional
semiconductor-based solar cells

00:04:55.810 --> 00:04:58.550
like this one here.

00:04:58.550 --> 00:05:00.840
So for those history
folks, I figured

00:05:00.840 --> 00:05:03.350
I would add a quick
at description.

00:05:03.350 --> 00:05:05.120
You typically see
the diode represented

00:05:05.120 --> 00:05:06.650
like this in an
equivalent circuit

00:05:06.650 --> 00:05:11.630
diagram, a little triangle
and a line orthogonal

00:05:11.630 --> 00:05:13.480
to the direction of
the current path.

00:05:13.480 --> 00:05:18.220
And does anybody know
where that comes from?

00:05:18.220 --> 00:05:19.620
No?

00:05:19.620 --> 00:05:20.280
All right.

00:05:20.280 --> 00:05:25.030
So back in the day
of that, we used

00:05:25.030 --> 00:05:28.151
to have vacuum tube components
for a lot of our-- I

00:05:28.151 --> 00:05:31.660
would say the discrete
components within our circuits.

00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:35.590
In the case of a diode, you
could envision a very simple

00:05:35.590 --> 00:05:39.290
one where you have a filament
that by thermionic emission

00:05:39.290 --> 00:05:41.630
heats electrons off
of the filament,

00:05:41.630 --> 00:05:46.050
and then they're collected by
this other collector up top.

00:05:46.050 --> 00:05:50.400
If you remember our etymology
in Greek, ana is above,

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:51.510
cata is below.

00:05:51.510 --> 00:05:52.470
Catatombs, right?

00:05:52.470 --> 00:05:53.950
Catatonic, below.

00:05:53.950 --> 00:05:56.520
So the anode up above is
collecting these electrons,

00:05:56.520 --> 00:05:58.510
and then the electron
flow is moving

00:05:58.510 --> 00:06:01.090
like this, which means that
our current flow, defined

00:06:01.090 --> 00:06:02.810
as the flow of
positive charge, is

00:06:02.810 --> 00:06:04.460
moving the opposite direction.

00:06:04.460 --> 00:06:07.950
And that's why we have a similar
representation right here

00:06:07.950 --> 00:06:09.260
from our vacuum technology.

00:06:09.260 --> 00:06:11.080
You could envision
also a point where

00:06:11.080 --> 00:06:13.100
the field is
concentrated at that tip

00:06:13.100 --> 00:06:15.910
and electrons are spreading off.

00:06:15.910 --> 00:06:17.437
So learning objectives.

00:06:17.437 --> 00:06:19.520
Today is going to be rather
intense, rather dense.

00:06:19.520 --> 00:06:24.650
And so we will be trying to hold
as much as possible in our RAM,

00:06:24.650 --> 00:06:27.840
so that by the end of class
we can really truly understand

00:06:27.840 --> 00:06:29.650
the solar cell as an entirety.

00:06:29.650 --> 00:06:32.190
If you get lost along
the way, come back

00:06:32.190 --> 00:06:33.510
to these learning objectives.

00:06:33.510 --> 00:06:35.780
They're like flag
posts along the way.

00:06:35.780 --> 00:06:38.284
So you can find yourself again.

00:06:38.284 --> 00:06:39.950
What we're going to
do first is describe

00:06:39.950 --> 00:06:41.832
how the conductivity
of a semiconductor

00:06:41.832 --> 00:06:43.790
can be modified by the
intentional introduction

00:06:43.790 --> 00:06:44.960
of dopants.

00:06:44.960 --> 00:06:46.630
What this means is
we're going to learn

00:06:46.630 --> 00:06:49.170
how to create the n
and the p over here.

00:06:52.380 --> 00:06:56.840
So if we look at a
semiconductor such as silicon--

00:06:56.840 --> 00:06:58.730
this is a little piece
of silicon right here.

00:06:58.730 --> 00:07:00.610
Here's a silicon-based
solar cell.

00:07:00.610 --> 00:07:02.992
It's a fairly easy
semiconductor to understand.

00:07:02.992 --> 00:07:04.700
It's what's called a
unary semiconductor.

00:07:04.700 --> 00:07:06.650
It means it's comprised
of one element.

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:08.440
Silicon right here in
the periodic table.

00:07:08.440 --> 00:07:10.940
This is just an excerpt
from the rightmost side

00:07:10.940 --> 00:07:12.590
of the periodic table.

00:07:12.590 --> 00:07:15.300
And silicon has 4
valence electrons.

00:07:15.300 --> 00:07:18.340
So it forms what are called
sp3 hybridized orbitals when

00:07:18.340 --> 00:07:19.510
it's in a crystal structure.

00:07:19.510 --> 00:07:23.460
It has four bonds with
its nearest neighbors,

00:07:23.460 --> 00:07:24.820
all of equivalent type.

00:07:24.820 --> 00:07:26.740
And those are covalent bonds.

00:07:26.740 --> 00:07:29.740
So you can envision that if
you were to introduce an atom

00:07:29.740 --> 00:07:32.200
and substitute out one
silicon atom in that lattice

00:07:32.200 --> 00:07:35.430
for something else that
has 5 valence electrons,

00:07:35.430 --> 00:07:39.450
such as a phosphorus, it's
almost of equivalent size.

00:07:39.450 --> 00:07:41.300
So those material
scientists in the room

00:07:41.300 --> 00:07:42.950
from the Hume-Rothery
rules, you should

00:07:42.950 --> 00:07:45.450
be able to estimate that the
miscibility is rather large.

00:07:45.450 --> 00:07:48.140
In other words, that you could
mix in a high concentration

00:07:48.140 --> 00:07:51.670
of phosphorus into your
silicon given the similar size

00:07:51.670 --> 00:07:54.420
and similar atomic structure.

00:07:54.420 --> 00:07:56.050
Electronic structure, rather.

00:07:56.050 --> 00:07:59.440
So you substitute here
a group 5 element.

00:07:59.440 --> 00:08:03.400
Silicon is a group 4 element, as
is carbon, germanium, and tin.

00:08:03.400 --> 00:08:05.480
So we substitute in
a group 5 element.

00:08:05.480 --> 00:08:08.670
Let's say a phosphorus atom in
for one of our silicon atoms

00:08:08.670 --> 00:08:09.810
right here.

00:08:09.810 --> 00:08:11.530
And this phosphorus
atom will have

00:08:11.530 --> 00:08:13.880
4 plus 1 valence electrons.

00:08:13.880 --> 00:08:15.660
So those 4 valence
electrons will

00:08:15.660 --> 00:08:18.300
bond to the silicon atoms,
the nearest neighbors.

00:08:18.300 --> 00:08:21.170
And that one extra valence
electron will be left over.

00:08:21.170 --> 00:08:22.745
It will have nobody to bond to.

00:08:22.745 --> 00:08:24.540
And we'll describe
mathematically

00:08:24.540 --> 00:08:26.710
what happens to that
electron in a minute.

00:08:26.710 --> 00:08:28.550
But in principle,
just intuitively you

00:08:28.550 --> 00:08:30.800
should be able to understand
that that electron should

00:08:30.800 --> 00:08:32.258
be able to be
removed rather easily

00:08:32.258 --> 00:08:34.920
and move around the
lattice with relative ease.

00:08:34.920 --> 00:08:37.419
Likewise, instead of moving one
to the right, if we move one

00:08:37.419 --> 00:08:39.600
to the left into our
group 3 column here,

00:08:39.600 --> 00:08:43.470
we can dope our material
with a boron atom, let's say.

00:08:43.470 --> 00:08:46.030
Substituting one silicon
atom for a boron atom.

00:08:46.030 --> 00:08:47.980
Boron has 3 valence electrons.

00:08:47.980 --> 00:08:51.830
Now, those 3 will form bonds
with the 3 silicon atoms.

00:08:51.830 --> 00:08:53.420
And then you'll
have a missing bond,

00:08:53.420 --> 00:08:55.600
a missing electron if you will.

00:08:55.600 --> 00:08:57.590
That will be a hole.

00:08:57.590 --> 00:09:00.240
So with phosphorus, or
group 5 elements in silicon,

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:03.290
we can dope the
material with electrons.

00:09:03.290 --> 00:09:05.390
And with group 3
elements in silicon,

00:09:05.390 --> 00:09:08.200
we can dope the
material with holes.

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:10.180
And this is interesting
because now we

00:09:10.180 --> 00:09:13.890
can arbitrarily change the
density of charge carriers

00:09:13.890 --> 00:09:15.370
in our bands.

00:09:15.370 --> 00:09:17.530
As long as these
holes and electrons

00:09:17.530 --> 00:09:20.320
can become dissociated
from the dopant atoms

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:21.980
and move freely
around the lattice.

00:09:21.980 --> 00:09:23.490
So that's a big
question, how easy

00:09:23.490 --> 00:09:27.300
is it to remove that electron
around the phosphorus atom?

00:09:27.300 --> 00:09:29.950
If you want to think
about this electron just

00:09:29.950 --> 00:09:32.950
from a quantum
mechanical sense, you

00:09:32.950 --> 00:09:36.319
could almost envision that
this electron is attracted

00:09:36.319 --> 00:09:38.360
to the phosphorus atom
because the phosphorus has

00:09:38.360 --> 00:09:41.440
one extra proton than
the silicon, right?

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:44.730
So it has a positive
charge here in the nucleus.

00:09:44.730 --> 00:09:46.180
And here's a negative charge.

00:09:46.180 --> 00:09:47.810
In net, they balance out.

00:09:47.810 --> 00:09:49.929
But if the electron
goes too far away,

00:09:49.929 --> 00:09:51.720
it will feel that
attractive potential back

00:09:51.720 --> 00:09:53.840
and be drawn back towards
the phosphorus atom.

00:09:53.840 --> 00:09:55.923
So the big question is,
what is the binding energy

00:09:55.923 --> 00:09:57.834
of that electron to
the phosphorus atom?

00:09:57.834 --> 00:09:59.250
And a simple way
to think about it

00:09:59.250 --> 00:10:02.010
is through a hydrogenic model.

00:10:02.010 --> 00:10:05.570
If you consider a hydrogen atom
to have an electron surrounding

00:10:05.570 --> 00:10:10.010
it, then that binding
energy is well-defined.

00:10:10.010 --> 00:10:13.230
But in the case of a phosphorus
atom within a silicon lattice,

00:10:13.230 --> 00:10:14.510
it's a little trickier.

00:10:14.510 --> 00:10:19.380
Because now we have to
worry about the electron

00:10:19.380 --> 00:10:22.120
screening coming from the
other elements in our lattice.

00:10:22.120 --> 00:10:25.420
And we also have to worry about
a property of the electron

00:10:25.420 --> 00:10:29.610
in a crystal, which changes
the mobility of that electron

00:10:29.610 --> 00:10:30.910
through the crystal.

00:10:30.910 --> 00:10:34.610
So what we do is we
treat this as a hydrogen

00:10:34.610 --> 00:10:38.814
atom, 13.6 eV binding energy.

00:10:38.814 --> 00:10:40.230
But then we do a
couple of things.

00:10:40.230 --> 00:10:41.604
We account for
electron screening

00:10:41.604 --> 00:10:44.134
and we account for what
we call effective mass.

00:10:44.134 --> 00:10:45.800
We'll get back to
this in a few lectures

00:10:45.800 --> 00:10:48.212
and describe exactly
what this is here.

00:10:48.212 --> 00:10:50.170
We need a little bit more
semiconductor physics

00:10:50.170 --> 00:10:51.850
to understand it
in its entirety.

00:10:51.850 --> 00:10:54.380
But think about an electron
moving in a crystal

00:10:54.380 --> 00:10:55.850
as moving differently
than moving

00:10:55.850 --> 00:10:57.310
in free space in a vacuum.

00:10:57.310 --> 00:10:59.340
That's what this
term here is about.

00:10:59.340 --> 00:11:01.740
This other term, the epsilon,
is rather straightforward.

00:11:01.740 --> 00:11:02.470
It's the electron screening.

00:11:02.470 --> 00:11:04.595
It's the fact that you have
so many other electrons

00:11:04.595 --> 00:11:06.730
in your system here that
screening the charges,

00:11:06.730 --> 00:11:10.420
screening the electron from
the extra positive charge

00:11:10.420 --> 00:11:12.110
in the nucleus here.

00:11:12.110 --> 00:11:15.140
And so it becomes easier for
that electron to move away.

00:11:15.140 --> 00:11:19.140
This is about a factor of
0.1, the effective mass.

00:11:19.140 --> 00:11:21.150
And that's about 1/100.

00:11:21.150 --> 00:11:23.210
And so overall, we're
reducing the binding energy

00:11:23.210 --> 00:11:28.490
by about a factor of 1,000 down
to about 10 m eV in practice.

00:11:28.490 --> 00:11:30.870
So if we were to run through
the calculation for silicon,

00:11:30.870 --> 00:11:33.520
the binding energy of that
electron around the phosphorus

00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:35.730
atom in the silicon lattice
would be around 10 m

00:11:35.730 --> 00:11:37.470
eV on that order.

00:11:37.470 --> 00:11:40.590
And that is very,
very small compared

00:11:40.590 --> 00:11:44.160
to the thermal energy in your
system, just kt, Boltzmann's

00:11:44.160 --> 00:11:46.334
constant times the
temperature in Kelvin,

00:11:46.334 --> 00:11:47.750
we have a thermal
energy somewhere

00:11:47.750 --> 00:11:49.540
on the order of 26 m eV.

00:11:49.540 --> 00:11:51.666
And that's enough to
dissociate that electron

00:11:51.666 --> 00:11:53.790
and allow it to move freely
throughout the lattice.

00:11:53.790 --> 00:11:54.625
Question?

00:11:54.625 --> 00:11:56.445
AUDIENCE: Is that
electron screening

00:11:56.445 --> 00:11:58.630
related to the [INAUDIBLE]
constant at all?

00:11:58.630 --> 00:12:00.410
PROFESSOR: Yes, absolutely.

00:12:00.410 --> 00:12:02.201
AUDIENCE: I just had
a [INAUDIBLE] question

00:12:02.201 --> 00:12:03.500
about the holes.

00:12:03.500 --> 00:12:07.560
So I understand that-- I can
imagine an electron moving

00:12:07.560 --> 00:12:09.340
around in the lattice.

00:12:09.340 --> 00:12:11.930
But I imagine that
a hole moving would

00:12:11.930 --> 00:12:17.668
be forming a bond-- breaking
and forming bonds over and over.

00:12:17.668 --> 00:12:19.858
Does that actually happen,
or are the electrons

00:12:19.858 --> 00:12:21.924
more free to move?

00:12:21.924 --> 00:12:22.590
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:12:22.590 --> 00:12:24.160
This is an excellent question.

00:12:24.160 --> 00:12:25.830
The question, if
I may paraphrase,

00:12:25.830 --> 00:12:28.240
relates to the hole and
electron mobilities.

00:12:28.240 --> 00:12:30.449
How easy is it for them to
move around the lattice?

00:12:30.449 --> 00:12:32.490
And typically, the hole
mobility is about a third

00:12:32.490 --> 00:12:34.200
of the electron
mobility in silicon.

00:12:34.200 --> 00:12:37.060
So absolutely, it is a
little bit more difficult

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:38.500
for those holes to move around.

00:12:38.500 --> 00:12:42.130
Holes, you may recall,
are quasi-particles.

00:12:42.130 --> 00:12:45.653
OK, so we have an
understanding of doping,

00:12:45.653 --> 00:12:47.870
a rough understanding
at this point.

00:12:47.870 --> 00:12:51.420
We understand that if we dope a
certain type of material, let's

00:12:51.420 --> 00:12:54.940
say our n-type material,
with phosphorus,

00:12:54.940 --> 00:12:57.000
we have an excess of electrons.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:59.120
And if we dope another
type of material

00:12:59.120 --> 00:13:03.160
with an excess of, say,
boron, we would then

00:13:03.160 --> 00:13:04.900
introduce a large
number of holes

00:13:04.900 --> 00:13:08.350
and the material might have
a majority conductivity

00:13:08.350 --> 00:13:09.100
through our holes.

00:13:09.100 --> 00:13:11.080
Hence, we call it p-type.

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:13.920
n and p comes from
negative and positive.

00:13:13.920 --> 00:13:15.790
Negative being the
electron charge

00:13:15.790 --> 00:13:17.660
and positive being
the hole charge.

00:13:17.660 --> 00:13:20.291
So that's where the n-
and p-type come from.

00:13:20.291 --> 00:13:21.340
Great.

00:13:21.340 --> 00:13:25.200
So now, pictorially
we're going to draw

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:30.800
a pn-junction or a junction with
our fixed and mobile charges.

00:13:30.800 --> 00:13:37.010
OK, so let's start out with a
simple review of Gauss' law.

00:13:37.010 --> 00:13:39.810
Spatially variant fixed charge
creates an electric field.

00:13:39.810 --> 00:13:41.130
What do I mean by that?

00:13:41.130 --> 00:13:43.870
I mean that if you have
a high concentration

00:13:43.870 --> 00:13:46.370
of fixed charge over here and
a lower concentration of fixed

00:13:46.370 --> 00:13:49.209
charge over here, an
electric field will develop.

00:13:49.209 --> 00:13:50.750
And that's the
expression right there

00:13:50.750 --> 00:13:55.190
that relates-- that describes
this in mathematical terms

00:13:55.190 --> 00:13:58.330
where we're using psi here
as our electric field.

00:13:58.330 --> 00:14:00.200
We're using psi instead of e.

00:14:00.200 --> 00:14:02.060
You probably remember
your physics textbooks

00:14:02.060 --> 00:14:04.060
using e as the electric
field because we're

00:14:04.060 --> 00:14:07.100
going to reserve that variable
for the electron energy.

00:14:07.100 --> 00:14:10.500
That will come in
several slides forward.

00:14:10.500 --> 00:14:12.580
So the charge
density will be given

00:14:12.580 --> 00:14:16.640
by that rho and the material
permittivity by our epsilon.

00:14:16.640 --> 00:14:18.690
And an example is
a capacitor here.

00:14:18.690 --> 00:14:21.710
All I've done is expanded
the dimensionality

00:14:21.710 --> 00:14:23.692
of the derivative here.

00:14:23.692 --> 00:14:24.900
I'm looking at the capacitor.

00:14:24.900 --> 00:14:26.490
I have fixed charge
on either side.

00:14:26.490 --> 00:14:29.850
And I have electric
field in between.

00:14:29.850 --> 00:14:35.010
Now, this right here, obviously
in the case of a capacity,

00:14:35.010 --> 00:14:36.670
you're under high vacuum.

00:14:36.670 --> 00:14:40.560
Just as a very quick aside,
this is-- I can't resist.

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:43.690
This is really an
interesting historical note.

00:14:43.690 --> 00:14:45.979
This space right here in
the diode as we recall,

00:14:45.979 --> 00:14:48.520
where you have the thermionic
emission of the electrons going

00:14:48.520 --> 00:14:50.853
off to the other plate, this
space right instead of here

00:14:50.853 --> 00:14:54.070
is called the space
charge region.

00:14:54.070 --> 00:14:55.290
Keep that name in mind.

00:14:55.290 --> 00:14:58.230
We're going to come back
to it in several slides.

00:14:58.230 --> 00:14:59.920
So a bit of history there.

00:14:59.920 --> 00:15:03.060
So we have the capacitor
as our prime example.

00:15:03.060 --> 00:15:05.310
We have fixed charge on
either side and electric field

00:15:05.310 --> 00:15:06.310
in between.

00:15:06.310 --> 00:15:08.770
And note that the charge
will move parallel

00:15:08.770 --> 00:15:10.100
to the electric field.

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:12.150
If there's no electric
field-- in other words,

00:15:12.150 --> 00:15:15.036
if we're just exciting
charge inside of a bare piece

00:15:15.036 --> 00:15:16.410
of silicon with
no electric field

00:15:16.410 --> 00:15:18.310
applied-- imagine
our batteries here

00:15:18.310 --> 00:15:20.090
are taken out of the circuit.

00:15:20.090 --> 00:15:21.970
We'll have simple
Brownian motion

00:15:21.970 --> 00:15:24.850
of those photo-excited electrons
until they decay back down

00:15:24.850 --> 00:15:26.200
into their ground state.

00:15:26.200 --> 00:15:28.187
However, if we apply
an electric field,

00:15:28.187 --> 00:15:29.520
now we have the Brownian motion.

00:15:29.520 --> 00:15:32.420
But superimposed on top
of it, a certain drift

00:15:32.420 --> 00:15:35.470
of the electrons in response
to that electric field.

00:15:35.470 --> 00:15:37.700
And we can describe this
mathematically as well.

00:15:37.700 --> 00:15:40.600
The drift currents for
holes and electrons being

00:15:40.600 --> 00:15:42.739
described by the charge q.

00:15:42.739 --> 00:15:44.280
Note that the charge
q is going to be

00:15:44.280 --> 00:15:47.660
different for the electrons
and the holes-- the same value,

00:15:47.660 --> 00:15:49.060
but negative or positive.

00:15:49.060 --> 00:15:53.430
The mobility of holes and
mobility of electrons.

00:15:53.430 --> 00:15:55.500
The density of
holes or electrons.

00:15:55.500 --> 00:15:58.380
And then finally, the
electric field right here.

00:15:58.380 --> 00:16:00.810
And the reason in this
equation you typically

00:16:00.810 --> 00:16:04.340
see the q's being
the same value here,

00:16:04.340 --> 00:16:06.932
although no minus
sign is put in front,

00:16:06.932 --> 00:16:08.640
is because under the
same electric field,

00:16:08.640 --> 00:16:11.056
you'll have electrons drifting
in this direction and holes

00:16:11.056 --> 00:16:13.980
drifting in the
opposite direction.

00:16:13.980 --> 00:16:17.600
So it's important to keep these
signs straight in your mind.

00:16:17.600 --> 00:16:18.675
Yeah, question?

00:16:18.675 --> 00:16:19.830
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:19.830 --> 00:16:20.746
PROFESSOR: Absolutely.

00:16:20.746 --> 00:16:22.460
So p and n denote
the concentrations

00:16:22.460 --> 00:16:24.870
of free electrons or
free hole-- actually,

00:16:24.870 --> 00:16:27.950
free holes for free
electrons, respectively.

00:16:27.950 --> 00:16:31.670
So you can almost think
of p as being synonymous

00:16:31.670 --> 00:16:36.710
with the density of boron atoms.

00:16:36.710 --> 00:16:39.450
If every hole is
ionized, meaning

00:16:39.450 --> 00:16:42.460
dissociated from the dopant
atom and free to move around

00:16:42.460 --> 00:16:45.256
the crystal, then
the density of holes

00:16:45.256 --> 00:16:46.630
and the density
of boron atoms is

00:16:46.630 --> 00:16:48.530
going to be almost identical.

00:16:48.530 --> 00:16:50.800
Likewise, for
phosphorus atoms and/or

00:16:50.800 --> 00:16:53.360
the donor atoms
and the electrons,

00:16:53.360 --> 00:16:56.860
you'll have almost
an equal number.

00:16:56.860 --> 00:16:58.710
So that's right here.

00:16:58.710 --> 00:17:00.962
The n is related to
the number of electrons

00:17:00.962 --> 00:17:02.670
that are free to move
around the crystal.

00:17:02.670 --> 00:17:06.630
The p, the density of holes
that are free to move around

00:17:06.630 --> 00:17:07.440
in the crystal.

00:17:07.440 --> 00:17:12.910
And these are given in units
of number of particles charge

00:17:12.910 --> 00:17:14.740
carriers per unit volume.

00:17:14.740 --> 00:17:16.619
So per centimeter
cubed, let's say.

00:17:16.619 --> 00:17:17.483
Question.

00:17:17.483 --> 00:17:21.347
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
you're creating more holes.

00:17:21.347 --> 00:17:23.659
So is that not on the
same order of magnitude

00:17:23.659 --> 00:17:25.700
as the number of holes
introduced by [INAUDIBLE]?

00:17:25.700 --> 00:17:26.866
PROFESSOR: Yeah, absolutely.

00:17:26.866 --> 00:17:31.170
So the density of holes and
electrons here in the dark

00:17:31.170 --> 00:17:34.190
is dictated by the
dopant density.

00:17:34.190 --> 00:17:34.870
Where are we?

00:17:34.870 --> 00:17:36.810
Right here, for instance,
the dopant density.

00:17:36.810 --> 00:17:40.620
If we add light, that's
a complicating factor.

00:17:40.620 --> 00:17:44.564
The intrinsic population
of electrons and holes

00:17:44.564 --> 00:17:46.730
and the dopant concentration
of electrons and holes,

00:17:46.730 --> 00:17:49.400
we are adding a photo-generated
population as well.

00:17:49.400 --> 00:17:51.700
Let's leave that
for next lecture

00:17:51.700 --> 00:17:52.980
and try to simplify things.

00:17:52.980 --> 00:17:55.410
So we just discussed
the diode in the dark.

00:17:55.410 --> 00:17:59.640
Perhaps we turn the light
off here just for effect.

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:02.312
So we're trying to take this
piece by piece, so that we

00:18:02.312 --> 00:18:04.270
can really construct
everything and not add too

00:18:04.270 --> 00:18:07.390
much into the pot at one time.

00:18:07.390 --> 00:18:10.890
I wanted to discuss the
notion of electron drift.

00:18:10.890 --> 00:18:12.530
And I also wanted to
review the concept

00:18:12.530 --> 00:18:15.459
of diffusion, which everyone
should be familiar with.

00:18:15.459 --> 00:18:17.500
This is the reason why
we're breathing right now,

00:18:17.500 --> 00:18:20.670
and why all the air
molecules aren't crowded

00:18:20.670 --> 00:18:22.100
into that corner of the room.

00:18:22.100 --> 00:18:25.590
It's because of Fick's law,
the process of diffusion.

00:18:25.590 --> 00:18:29.630
If we have a concentration of
a particular species in one

00:18:29.630 --> 00:18:33.850
spatial location, the natural
tendency through random motion

00:18:33.850 --> 00:18:35.880
is for that concentration
to distribute

00:18:35.880 --> 00:18:38.210
itself equally throughout.

00:18:38.210 --> 00:18:40.960
And this is described
very nicely by Fick's law.

00:18:40.960 --> 00:18:44.040
If we want to describe
a current to it,

00:18:44.040 --> 00:18:46.160
we would then describe
the current of holes

00:18:46.160 --> 00:18:50.000
and the current of electrons
by, again, the charge.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:54.160
The diffusivity, this is
a quantity typically given

00:18:54.160 --> 00:18:56.920
in units of centimeters
squared per second.

00:18:56.920 --> 00:18:58.080
And the gradient.

00:18:58.080 --> 00:19:00.750
In other words, the
concentration gradient.

00:19:00.750 --> 00:19:02.720
In this case, in one dimension.

00:19:02.720 --> 00:19:06.360
And that, again, should
be review for most folks

00:19:06.360 --> 00:19:07.600
from physics.

00:19:07.600 --> 00:19:09.720
And so we can see here
two different methods

00:19:09.720 --> 00:19:12.597
of currents, two different
methods of current flow inside

00:19:12.597 --> 00:19:13.680
of a semiconductor device.

00:19:13.680 --> 00:19:18.670
We can have diffusion
or we can have drift.

00:19:18.670 --> 00:19:20.660
Drift occurs when
there's an electric field

00:19:20.660 --> 00:19:26.500
present and diffusion occurs
when-- well, in this case,

00:19:26.500 --> 00:19:28.900
diffusion can occur in the
absence of an electric field

00:19:28.900 --> 00:19:32.350
simply when there is a
concentration gradient present.

00:19:32.350 --> 00:19:34.840
So we can envision,
just quickly,

00:19:34.840 --> 00:19:36.970
that if we have an
electric field confined

00:19:36.970 --> 00:19:39.200
to a certain region of
our solar cell device,

00:19:39.200 --> 00:19:42.380
the electric field will be
dominant in one portion.

00:19:42.380 --> 00:19:44.710
And if the rest of
our device we don't

00:19:44.710 --> 00:19:47.930
have a strong electric field,
but the electrons nevertheless

00:19:47.930 --> 00:19:49.530
can sense the electric
field far away

00:19:49.530 --> 00:19:51.370
because of the
concentration gradient,

00:19:51.370 --> 00:19:53.870
diffusion can drive
those electrons--

00:19:53.870 --> 00:19:57.300
can drive those electron
toward the electric field.

00:19:57.300 --> 00:20:01.190
So in our solar cell device,
the ratio of drift and diffusion

00:20:01.190 --> 00:20:03.650
current will change as
a function of distance

00:20:03.650 --> 00:20:08.900
from the pn-junction,
from the built-in field.

00:20:08.900 --> 00:20:12.600
OK, so I want everybody
to upload into their RAM

00:20:12.600 --> 00:20:15.180
the checkerboard example
that we went through.

00:20:15.180 --> 00:20:18.570
Because this will be important
for understanding the next few

00:20:18.570 --> 00:20:20.510
slides.

00:20:20.510 --> 00:20:22.560
So let's imagine these
n-and p-type materials are

00:20:22.560 --> 00:20:24.490
in contact, but there's
this imaginary barrier

00:20:24.490 --> 00:20:25.281
right between them.

00:20:27.680 --> 00:20:31.560
Here are p-type materials,
here are n-type materials.

00:20:31.560 --> 00:20:33.690
And let's parse
through this figure.

00:20:33.690 --> 00:20:35.530
Let's dwell, just a minute.

00:20:35.530 --> 00:20:37.010
So we have this
imaginary boundary

00:20:37.010 --> 00:20:39.650
between p-type material over
here and n-type material.

00:20:39.650 --> 00:20:41.720
The boundary is right
here in the middle.

00:20:41.720 --> 00:20:44.800
The blue dots here
are representing

00:20:44.800 --> 00:20:47.590
mobile holes, holes that
are free to move around

00:20:47.590 --> 00:20:48.870
the material.

00:20:48.870 --> 00:20:51.800
And while there's this
imaginary barrier here,

00:20:51.800 --> 00:20:53.940
these holes are just
moving in Brownian motion.

00:20:53.940 --> 00:20:55.680
There's no net current.

00:20:55.680 --> 00:20:58.100
There's no net charge flow.

00:20:58.100 --> 00:21:01.710
These minus signs that are left
behind are the boron atoms.

00:21:01.710 --> 00:21:05.160
The boron atoms have one
less proton in their nucleus

00:21:05.160 --> 00:21:08.000
than the silicon atoms do.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:10.970
And so the hole plus
the negative charge

00:21:10.970 --> 00:21:14.050
that's within the boron
atom core if you will,

00:21:14.050 --> 00:21:16.280
that combination is neutral.

00:21:16.280 --> 00:21:20.100
So we haven't perturbed the net
charge of the entire system.

00:21:20.100 --> 00:21:22.630
But locally, if we draw a
little circle around these two

00:21:22.630 --> 00:21:25.360
for instance, the boron
atom that's fixed,

00:21:25.360 --> 00:21:26.300
that's not moving.

00:21:26.300 --> 00:21:28.100
The boron atom is bound to
the neighboring silicon atoms.

00:21:28.100 --> 00:21:29.420
It's not moving around.

00:21:29.420 --> 00:21:32.410
And the hole, which is free
to move around the material,

00:21:32.410 --> 00:21:34.790
now we have net
charge neutrality.

00:21:34.790 --> 00:21:36.380
But if that hole
moves too far away,

00:21:36.380 --> 00:21:40.940
then you could have
a field building up.

00:21:40.940 --> 00:21:42.680
On the other side, very similar.

00:21:42.680 --> 00:21:45.250
Here we have phosphorus atoms
embedded within our silicon

00:21:45.250 --> 00:21:46.070
lattice.

00:21:46.070 --> 00:21:48.677
The phosphorus atoms have one
extra proton in their nucleus

00:21:48.677 --> 00:21:49.760
than the silicon atoms do.

00:21:49.760 --> 00:21:53.980
Hence, we denote that as a
positive charge right here.

00:21:53.980 --> 00:21:57.530
And there's an extra electron
associated with the phosphorus

00:21:57.530 --> 00:21:58.220
atoms.

00:21:58.220 --> 00:22:01.180
Now as those electrons move
around, when it's in isolation,

00:22:01.180 --> 00:22:02.960
again, there's no
net charge flow.

00:22:02.960 --> 00:22:04.300
There's no current.

00:22:04.300 --> 00:22:09.840
And we have a situation
of net charge neutrality.

00:22:09.840 --> 00:22:11.880
Question is, what
happens if we remove

00:22:11.880 --> 00:22:14.260
the barrier in between the two?

00:22:14.260 --> 00:22:15.990
Let me ask you just
a basic question.

00:22:15.990 --> 00:22:19.130
Would the phosphorus atoms
diffuse over to this side?

00:22:19.130 --> 00:22:19.970
AUDIENCE: No.

00:22:19.970 --> 00:22:22.345
PROFESSOR: Probably not,
because the phosphorus atoms are

00:22:22.345 --> 00:22:24.280
bound to 4 silicon neighbors.

00:22:24.280 --> 00:22:26.540
Those bonds are really
tough and it's probably not

00:22:26.540 --> 00:22:28.270
going to break.

00:22:28.270 --> 00:22:30.990
Unless you heat it up to
a pretty high temperature.

00:22:30.990 --> 00:22:32.809
But the electrons are
free to move around.

00:22:32.809 --> 00:22:34.100
They're in the conduction band.

00:22:34.100 --> 00:22:35.910
They're able to move.

00:22:35.910 --> 00:22:38.290
And because the binding
energy to the phosphorus atoms

00:22:38.290 --> 00:22:41.849
is on that order of
10 m EV on that order,

00:22:41.849 --> 00:22:43.640
the thermal energy here
at room temperature

00:22:43.640 --> 00:22:45.780
is enough to dissociate
them, and to allow

00:22:45.780 --> 00:22:49.140
those electrons to move away
from the phosphorus atom thanks

00:22:49.140 --> 00:22:51.400
to the screening potential
of the surrounding lattice

00:22:51.400 --> 00:22:54.370
and thanks to the fact that the
electrons inside of a crystal

00:22:54.370 --> 00:22:58.450
are more easily-- can more
easily move than in vacuum.

00:22:58.450 --> 00:23:01.180
So when we remove that
boundary in between,

00:23:01.180 --> 00:23:02.950
what begins to happen?

00:23:02.950 --> 00:23:04.220
So we've removed the boundary.

00:23:04.220 --> 00:23:06.610
We have these two materials
in direct contact.

00:23:06.610 --> 00:23:09.400
The nuclei are not moving.

00:23:09.400 --> 00:23:12.140
The fixed charge associated
with the boron atoms

00:23:12.140 --> 00:23:14.830
in this side and the
phosphorus atoms on that side

00:23:14.830 --> 00:23:16.160
are not moving.

00:23:16.160 --> 00:23:20.250
However, the instant you remove
this boundary in between,

00:23:20.250 --> 00:23:22.430
there is a high concentration
of electrons over here

00:23:22.430 --> 00:23:24.970
and a very low concentration
of electrons over there, which

00:23:24.970 --> 00:23:28.929
means that you will have
a diffusion process.

00:23:28.929 --> 00:23:31.220
So the concentration gradient
drives the electrons over

00:23:31.220 --> 00:23:32.510
to this side.

00:23:32.510 --> 00:23:35.340
Likewise, holes are being
driven from here over to here.

00:23:35.340 --> 00:23:36.580
Now, notice what happens.

00:23:36.580 --> 00:23:38.940
Holes carry a positive charge.

00:23:38.940 --> 00:23:41.450
The fixed charge from the
phosphorus is also positive.

00:23:41.450 --> 00:23:43.430
So you have a buildup
of net positive charge

00:23:43.430 --> 00:23:45.620
on this side of the junction.

00:23:45.620 --> 00:23:47.570
Electrons are negative
charge carriers.

00:23:47.570 --> 00:23:49.880
The boron atoms have a
net negative charge here.

00:23:49.880 --> 00:23:51.421
And so you have a
net negative charge

00:23:51.421 --> 00:23:52.770
building up on this side.

00:23:52.770 --> 00:23:54.640
And now you have
a field beginning

00:23:54.640 --> 00:23:57.150
to develop, an electric field.

00:23:57.150 --> 00:24:00.220
And at some point, this
built-in electric field

00:24:00.220 --> 00:24:02.640
will counteract the
diffusion process.

00:24:02.640 --> 00:24:05.760
The diffusion current is driving
electrons in this direction,

00:24:05.760 --> 00:24:08.720
but the field will be driving
them back the other way.

00:24:08.720 --> 00:24:12.360
And it's that equilibrium that
establishes the pn-junction.

00:24:12.360 --> 00:24:14.200
It's that equilibrium
that defines

00:24:14.200 --> 00:24:18.820
the width of this region here,
this transition region, which

00:24:18.820 --> 00:24:20.390
comes in a variety of names.

00:24:20.390 --> 00:24:22.930
The transition region is also
called the depletion region.

00:24:22.930 --> 00:24:26.740
And it's also called
the space charge region.

00:24:26.740 --> 00:24:31.610
Interesting how these words
and terms come back into use.

00:24:31.610 --> 00:24:37.200
So that's the essence of the
formation of this junction.

00:24:37.200 --> 00:24:39.100
We have this
diffusion process that

00:24:39.100 --> 00:24:43.380
drives the carriers from
this side into this side.

00:24:43.380 --> 00:24:45.330
And then as we have the
electrons moving over

00:24:45.330 --> 00:24:51.032
here, and summing to
the boron nuclei that

00:24:51.032 --> 00:24:52.740
are left behind once
the holes, likewise,

00:24:52.740 --> 00:24:54.156
have moved over
to the other side.

00:24:54.156 --> 00:24:56.610
We have a buildup of net
negative charge on this side,

00:24:56.610 --> 00:24:59.040
a buildup of net positive
charge on that side,

00:24:59.040 --> 00:25:04.810
and the establishment of
a built-in electric field.

00:25:04.810 --> 00:25:06.120
That's cool.

00:25:06.120 --> 00:25:08.430
It takes a while
to really get it.

00:25:08.430 --> 00:25:10.460
And so the chessboard
example was brilliant.

00:25:10.460 --> 00:25:12.100
I thank Joe for that.

00:25:12.100 --> 00:25:14.000
And hopefully, this
as well reinforces

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:16.250
several of those concepts.

00:25:16.250 --> 00:25:19.250
And it might take some time
studying it on your own

00:25:19.250 --> 00:25:21.340
or setting up special
office hours with Joe

00:25:21.340 --> 00:25:23.380
or coming to my office
hours on Mondays.

00:25:23.380 --> 00:25:26.220
But whatever it takes, make
sure that you understand

00:25:26.220 --> 00:25:30.040
this concept well--
the fundamental--

00:25:30.040 --> 00:25:31.975
gaining an intuition
about the concept.

00:25:31.975 --> 00:25:33.710
We'll be getting
into the math soon.

00:25:33.710 --> 00:25:35.751
And if you don't have a
good, solid understanding

00:25:35.751 --> 00:25:39.920
of the intuition of where
charges are moving around,

00:25:39.920 --> 00:25:44.760
it becomes less easy, let's
say, to really get the math.

00:25:44.760 --> 00:25:48.690
So we have a buildup
of net charge

00:25:48.690 --> 00:25:50.040
on either side of the junction.

00:25:50.040 --> 00:25:51.790
We have a buildup of
net negative charge

00:25:51.790 --> 00:25:53.499
on one side of the
junction and a buildup

00:25:53.499 --> 00:25:55.873
of net positive charge on the
other side of the junction.

00:25:55.873 --> 00:25:57.400
And this line
right here is meant

00:25:57.400 --> 00:26:00.990
to represent that dividing
line where the two materials

00:26:00.990 --> 00:26:02.640
initially came together.

00:26:02.640 --> 00:26:06.420
So the dashed line is meant
to represent the real charge

00:26:06.420 --> 00:26:11.050
distribution and the
boxed colored rectangles,

00:26:11.050 --> 00:26:14.340
the rectilinear boxes, are meant
to represent an approximation

00:26:14.340 --> 00:26:17.140
that we'll use for the
rest of today's class.

00:26:17.140 --> 00:26:19.190
We're making successive
approximations

00:26:19.190 --> 00:26:23.070
here because we want the
mathematics to be manageable.

00:26:23.070 --> 00:26:29.830
You can, of course, discretize
this entire material

00:26:29.830 --> 00:26:32.590
in one dimension, for instance,
and do a finite element

00:26:32.590 --> 00:26:33.290
solution.

00:26:33.290 --> 00:26:36.000
We'll show you the equations
that you can use to do that

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:37.960
later on in today's class.

00:26:37.960 --> 00:26:40.080
So we have the net
charge distribution

00:26:40.080 --> 00:26:44.150
on either side of the
junction shown here.

00:26:44.150 --> 00:26:49.310
We also have, as a result
of that net charge,

00:26:49.310 --> 00:26:50.460
an electric field.

00:26:50.460 --> 00:26:55.130
And this goes back to Gauss'
law, or the derivative form

00:26:55.130 --> 00:26:55.670
there of.

00:26:55.670 --> 00:27:00.990
And so we have here a built-in
electric field as you can see.

00:27:00.990 --> 00:27:04.314
And the field reaches a maximum
right here in the middle.

00:27:04.314 --> 00:27:05.480
So that kind of makes sense.

00:27:05.480 --> 00:27:07.490
If you're too far away
from that junction,

00:27:07.490 --> 00:27:09.740
you're not going to-- if
you're a charge carrier,

00:27:09.740 --> 00:27:11.220
you're not going
to see the field.

00:27:11.220 --> 00:27:13.700
But if you're right there in
the middle of that junction,

00:27:13.700 --> 00:27:14.950
that field is going
to be very strong.

00:27:14.950 --> 00:27:16.783
You'll be swept out of
there pretty quickly.

00:27:16.783 --> 00:27:19.030
That's why the field
reaches a maximum right here

00:27:19.030 --> 00:27:19.730
in the middle.

00:27:19.730 --> 00:27:22.220
So that intuitively
makes a lot of sense.

00:27:22.220 --> 00:27:27.260
Now, if we take one further
integral of the electric field,

00:27:27.260 --> 00:27:29.340
here the electric
field, arc psi.

00:27:29.340 --> 00:27:34.020
If we integrate our arc psi,
we will get the potential.

00:27:34.020 --> 00:27:37.500
And this potential right
here essentially follows

00:27:37.500 --> 00:27:40.830
this wave-like
curve, where you have

00:27:40.830 --> 00:27:42.970
a lower potential on
this side and a higher

00:27:42.970 --> 00:27:44.460
potential on that side.

00:27:44.460 --> 00:27:47.570
And if we take this potential
and translate it into something

00:27:47.570 --> 00:27:50.580
that we can understand,
which is electron energy,

00:27:50.580 --> 00:27:52.790
by multiplying the
potential by q.

00:27:52.790 --> 00:27:55.150
And q in the case of an
electron is a negative number.

00:27:55.150 --> 00:27:57.614
That's why we're flipping this.

00:27:57.614 --> 00:27:59.030
So we're flipping
this upside down

00:27:59.030 --> 00:28:00.738
because we're multiplying
this value here

00:28:00.738 --> 00:28:02.180
by a negative number.

00:28:02.180 --> 00:28:04.200
Now, what we can
see is that there's

00:28:04.200 --> 00:28:07.590
an energy gain for the electron
by going from the p-side

00:28:07.590 --> 00:28:08.380
to the n-side.

00:28:10.920 --> 00:28:12.870
This is the electron energy.

00:28:12.870 --> 00:28:15.780
Obviously, if you give
them an opportunity,

00:28:15.780 --> 00:28:18.310
all the electrons would want
to come down to this side.

00:28:18.310 --> 00:28:21.944
But why wouldn't all of
them come down over here?

00:28:21.944 --> 00:28:23.282
AUDIENCE: Because of diffusion.

00:28:23.282 --> 00:28:24.615
PROFESSOR: Because of diffusion.

00:28:24.615 --> 00:28:26.670
So there's that balance
of the two effects.

00:28:26.670 --> 00:28:29.360
So there is a net energy
gain for the electrons,

00:28:29.360 --> 00:28:32.426
but diffusion is what's
driving some of the electrons

00:28:32.426 --> 00:28:34.300
back across the other
side of the junction is

00:28:34.300 --> 00:28:39.340
that equilibrium, which is
establishing the final energy

00:28:39.340 --> 00:28:42.660
band diagram of the pn-junction,
which is really looking

00:28:42.660 --> 00:28:44.950
something very much like that.

00:28:44.950 --> 00:28:49.220
So this right here describes
for you how you go from atoms

00:28:49.220 --> 00:28:51.240
and charge carriers
up at the top

00:28:51.240 --> 00:28:55.450
to charge distribution, electric
field, potential, and finally

00:28:55.450 --> 00:28:56.980
electron energy.

00:28:56.980 --> 00:28:58.006
Yes.

00:28:58.006 --> 00:28:59.683
AUDIENCE: Are
these four diagrams

00:28:59.683 --> 00:29:01.615
specifically for electrons?

00:29:04.513 --> 00:29:07.411
Would the hole
ones be [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:07.411 --> 00:29:08.860
the reverse of that?

00:29:08.860 --> 00:29:13.150
PROFESSOR: So if you wanted to
look in terms of hole energy,

00:29:13.150 --> 00:29:15.690
this equation here
would be equally valid,

00:29:15.690 --> 00:29:17.441
but your charge would
be a positive value.

00:29:17.441 --> 00:29:20.023
And so you'd have a curve that
looked very similar to this one

00:29:20.023 --> 00:29:22.560
right here, where there'd be a
net energy gain for the holes

00:29:22.560 --> 00:29:24.360
to go on to the other side.

00:29:24.360 --> 00:29:27.980
And that's what establishes
the separation of charge.

00:29:27.980 --> 00:29:30.890
AUDIENCE: So the bottom one is
the only one that would change

00:29:30.890 --> 00:29:31.547
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:29:31.547 --> 00:29:32.630
PROFESSOR: That's correct.

00:29:32.630 --> 00:29:33.250
Yep.

00:29:33.250 --> 00:29:35.569
Everything else identical.

00:29:35.569 --> 00:29:37.360
So this is important,
this electron energy.

00:29:37.360 --> 00:29:40.380
And this jump right here
confuses a lot of folks.

00:29:40.380 --> 00:29:43.290
Because in books, they don't
often describe very clearly

00:29:43.290 --> 00:29:46.030
what is potential
and what is energy,

00:29:46.030 --> 00:29:48.230
almost using those two
terms interchangeably.

00:29:48.230 --> 00:29:50.850
But it's that cue, the
fact that the electron has

00:29:50.850 --> 00:29:54.560
a negative charge that
sets things right.

00:29:54.560 --> 00:29:56.640
OK, this is pretty important.

00:29:56.640 --> 00:29:58.330
This is the foundation,
the fundamental,

00:29:58.330 --> 00:30:01.440
of how a pn-junction
comes into being.

00:30:01.440 --> 00:30:03.920
And the summary of
our understanding

00:30:03.920 --> 00:30:07.550
so far is that when
the light-- here we go.

00:30:07.550 --> 00:30:09.850
When light creates an
electron-hole pair,

00:30:09.850 --> 00:30:13.360
a pn-junction can separate the
positive and negative charges

00:30:13.360 --> 00:30:15.660
because of the built-in
electric field.

00:30:15.660 --> 00:30:17.332
Let me repeat that
one more time.

00:30:17.332 --> 00:30:19.040
When light creates an
electron-hole pair,

00:30:19.040 --> 00:30:20.675
a pn-junction
potentially can separate

00:30:20.675 --> 00:30:22.050
the positive and
negative charges

00:30:22.050 --> 00:30:24.150
because of that
built-in electric field.

00:30:24.150 --> 00:30:28.040
For very small
light intensities,

00:30:28.040 --> 00:30:29.870
very small light
intensities, such

00:30:29.870 --> 00:30:33.770
that you can think of that
photo-generated carrier

00:30:33.770 --> 00:30:36.330
as a perturbation to the
system, not fundamentally

00:30:36.330 --> 00:30:39.526
altering the energy levels
yet-- it does eventually happen.

00:30:39.526 --> 00:30:41.150
But if you have, say,
one photon coming

00:30:41.150 --> 00:30:42.880
into your material
exciting electron

00:30:42.880 --> 00:30:45.690
over here, that
electron can move down,

00:30:45.690 --> 00:30:48.010
can be swept out of
the device, because

00:30:48.010 --> 00:30:50.370
of that built-in electric field.

00:30:50.370 --> 00:30:54.600
Again, assuming that we
have a very small impact

00:30:54.600 --> 00:30:57.260
on the electrostatic
[INAUDIBLE] system

00:30:57.260 --> 00:30:58.880
that it's just a
small perturbation,

00:30:58.880 --> 00:31:00.840
maybe one single
electron in our system

00:31:00.840 --> 00:31:03.330
is not going to affect you
much because we have 10

00:31:03.330 --> 00:31:07.560
to the 23 or so atoms
per cubic centimeter.

00:31:07.560 --> 00:31:09.980
We have a very small
perturbation to our system,

00:31:09.980 --> 00:31:13.496
that charge carrier will
be swept out very quickly.

00:31:13.496 --> 00:31:15.245
The built-in electric
field is established

00:31:15.245 --> 00:31:19.310
at a pn-junction because of the
balance of electron and hole

00:31:19.310 --> 00:31:21.330
drift and diffusion currents.

00:31:21.330 --> 00:31:24.000
Let me be more precise about
this one point right here.

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:25.010
Because the built-in
electric field

00:31:25.010 --> 00:31:26.240
is established at a
pn-junction because

00:31:26.240 --> 00:31:28.198
of the balance of electron
drift and diffusion.

00:31:28.198 --> 00:31:29.290
We talked about that.

00:31:29.290 --> 00:31:31.500
But hole drift and
diffusion as well.

00:31:31.500 --> 00:31:36.040
So if you go back over to here,
notice how the electron drift

00:31:36.040 --> 00:31:40.970
and diffusion are opposed and
equal and opposite to the hole

00:31:40.970 --> 00:31:42.570
diffusion and drift.

00:31:42.570 --> 00:31:44.960
So let's think about it
from this perspective

00:31:44.960 --> 00:31:47.190
right back here.

00:31:47.190 --> 00:31:48.890
This is clear, our
electron diffusion

00:31:48.890 --> 00:31:50.600
is going in that
direction because we

00:31:50.600 --> 00:31:52.183
have a high concentration
of electrons

00:31:52.183 --> 00:31:54.550
that tend to move toward the
low-concentration regime.

00:31:54.550 --> 00:31:56.770
So our electron
diffusion current

00:31:56.770 --> 00:31:58.840
is pointing toward the left.

00:31:58.840 --> 00:32:02.290
Our hole diffusion current
is pointing to the right.

00:32:02.290 --> 00:32:06.510
And the hole drift current,
because of this built-in field,

00:32:06.510 --> 00:32:08.570
is pointing opposite
the hole diffusion.

00:32:08.570 --> 00:32:11.400
So the hole drift current
will be pointing to the left.

00:32:11.400 --> 00:32:13.330
Whereas, the electron
drift current

00:32:13.330 --> 00:32:15.010
would be pointing to the right.

00:32:15.010 --> 00:32:17.101
So we have, in total,
four currents here.

00:32:17.101 --> 00:32:19.350
The way to think about it
would be, for example, let's

00:32:19.350 --> 00:32:20.660
take the electrons first.

00:32:20.660 --> 00:32:24.850
Electron drift or electron
diffusion and drift counteract.

00:32:24.850 --> 00:32:26.660
And then you can take the holes.

00:32:26.660 --> 00:32:30.190
Hole diffusion and
drift counteract.

00:32:30.190 --> 00:32:31.480
They're all balanced.

00:32:31.480 --> 00:32:35.400
And this is resulting in
zero net current flow when

00:32:35.400 --> 00:32:38.930
you have no illumination and
no external field applied

00:32:38.930 --> 00:32:41.308
to that device.

00:32:41.308 --> 00:32:44.275
That's pretty nifty.

00:32:44.275 --> 00:32:46.150
So the built-in electric
field is established

00:32:46.150 --> 00:32:48.420
at the pn-junction because
of the balance of drift

00:32:48.420 --> 00:32:50.820
and diffusion current for
both electrons and holes.

00:32:54.910 --> 00:32:56.840
So we have a small
in-class exercise.

00:32:56.840 --> 00:32:58.780
I'd like you to take out these.

00:32:58.780 --> 00:33:00.756
And I'd like you
to work in pairs.

00:33:00.756 --> 00:33:02.880
So that if anybody reaches
a small stumbling block,

00:33:02.880 --> 00:33:06.440
you can help each other
work through the problems.

00:33:06.440 --> 00:33:10.510
So first off, let's focus on
this upper left-hand portion

00:33:10.510 --> 00:33:12.700
right here as shown right there.

00:33:12.700 --> 00:33:14.700
This is a replica of
the sheet that you

00:33:14.700 --> 00:33:16.550
should have in front of you.

00:33:16.550 --> 00:33:19.720
So what we're doing is we're
dividing-- we're considering

00:33:19.720 --> 00:33:21.990
the pn-junction under no bias.

00:33:21.990 --> 00:33:24.730
That means that we're
not applying a battery

00:33:24.730 --> 00:33:26.200
to our pn-junction.

00:33:26.200 --> 00:33:28.920
So we have a pn-junction and
we don't attach a battery

00:33:28.920 --> 00:33:29.420
in series.

00:33:29.420 --> 00:33:32.690
We just have the pn-junction
under zero bias conditions.

00:33:32.690 --> 00:33:36.390
So the way we'd represent that
in that equivalent or model

00:33:36.390 --> 00:33:38.990
circuit diagram
right here is notice

00:33:38.990 --> 00:33:41.710
how we have these
little lines extending

00:33:41.710 --> 00:33:44.230
from the p- and the
n-regions and going above.

00:33:44.230 --> 00:33:46.246
Those represent the
external circuit outside

00:33:46.246 --> 00:33:47.120
of the actual device.

00:33:47.120 --> 00:33:49.510
The device would be
this one right here

00:33:49.510 --> 00:33:51.490
where we have p and our n.

00:33:51.490 --> 00:33:53.490
We have our positive
and negative charges

00:33:53.490 --> 00:33:57.340
here representing the
charges that have built up

00:33:57.340 --> 00:33:59.380
in that space charge
region that are creating

00:33:59.380 --> 00:34:00.707
the built-in electric field.

00:34:00.707 --> 00:34:03.040
And under no bias conditions--
I'll give you the answer.

00:34:03.040 --> 00:34:04.340
It's pretty straightforward.

00:34:04.340 --> 00:34:05.820
We would just draw
a straight line

00:34:05.820 --> 00:34:08.810
across right there bridging that
external circuit because there

00:34:08.810 --> 00:34:10.139
is no external bias.

00:34:10.139 --> 00:34:12.300
There is no battery applied.

00:34:12.300 --> 00:34:16.650
And so from an energy band
diagram, e versus x, for e

00:34:16.650 --> 00:34:19.420
being the electron
energy in this case.

00:34:19.420 --> 00:34:21.170
And our p-type material
being on this side

00:34:21.170 --> 00:34:23.280
and our n-type material
being on that side,

00:34:23.280 --> 00:34:26.630
let's draw the energy band
diagram, just like we've done

00:34:26.630 --> 00:34:28.949
or we've alluded to so far.

00:34:28.949 --> 00:34:32.120
Sketch out the energy band
diagram for this pn-junction.

