00:40:29.900 --> 00:40:32.920
to go from battery to
electron energy band diagram

00:40:32.920 --> 00:40:37.841
is to follow the same sequence
that we did over here.

00:40:37.841 --> 00:40:39.590
And if you're thinking
battery, and you're

00:40:39.590 --> 00:40:41.173
thinking positive
and negative, you're

00:40:41.173 --> 00:40:45.160
shifting the potential of one
side relative to the other.

00:40:45.160 --> 00:40:49.336
Then, take that potential shift
and flip it for the electron.

00:40:49.336 --> 00:40:53.380
AUDIENCE: I follow why the
diagrams are the way they are.

00:40:53.380 --> 00:40:58.750
But is it conceptually accurate
to think of the negative side

00:40:58.750 --> 00:41:01.628
as putting more electrons
into the n-side?

00:41:01.628 --> 00:41:02.530
PROFESSOR: One could.

00:41:02.530 --> 00:41:03.750
AUDIENCE: Like
injecting carriers?

00:41:03.750 --> 00:41:04.390
PROFESSOR: The way
I prefer to think

00:41:04.390 --> 00:41:06.230
about it is that you're
changing the energy

00:41:06.230 --> 00:41:08.500
levels, the potential one
relative to the other.

00:41:08.500 --> 00:41:10.780
And as a consequence, you
have more electrons flowing

00:41:10.780 --> 00:41:13.420
from that n-side to the p-side.

00:41:13.420 --> 00:41:16.050
And that's what's pulling the
current through the circuit.

00:41:19.930 --> 00:41:23.100
It's almost a tail wagging
dog, dog wagging tail.

00:41:23.100 --> 00:41:25.250
But I would take a
slight preference

00:41:25.250 --> 00:41:28.360
toward understanding it from
the perspective of if you change

00:41:28.360 --> 00:41:30.206
the potential one
relative to the other,

00:41:30.206 --> 00:41:31.580
and allow for a
greater diffusion

00:41:31.580 --> 00:41:35.250
current, that motion of
electrons, the electron moving

00:41:35.250 --> 00:41:37.880
from here to here,
