00:44:47.510 --> 00:44:50.370
into doing learning objective
number 3 on your own,

00:44:50.370 --> 00:44:52.339
before even describing the math.

00:44:52.339 --> 00:44:54.630
But I will show you the
mathematics as well so that you

00:44:54.630 --> 00:44:56.480
have the complete picture.

00:44:56.480 --> 00:44:58.080
We have the diffusion current.

00:44:58.080 --> 00:44:59.800
This is the essence
of diffusion current.

00:44:59.800 --> 00:45:01.820
We talked about Fick's
law as well for holes

00:45:01.820 --> 00:45:03.270
and for electrons.

00:45:03.270 --> 00:45:04.740
We have our drift current.

00:45:04.740 --> 00:45:06.710
We spoke about the nature
of the drift current

00:45:06.710 --> 00:45:09.100
as well for holes and electrons.

00:45:09.100 --> 00:45:11.440
And we know that by
combining the two,

00:45:11.440 --> 00:45:14.170
we can describe the net current
flow across a pn-junction.

00:45:14.170 --> 00:45:17.830
So by combining the two, by
combining drift and diffusion--

00:45:17.830 --> 00:45:20.870
drift and diffusion for
electrons and holes--

00:45:20.870 --> 00:45:25.220
we can describe the current
flow across that pn-junction.

00:45:25.220 --> 00:45:28.350
So when the electric
field is large,

00:45:28.350 --> 00:45:30.370
the drift current term
is going to dominate.

00:45:30.370 --> 00:45:31.960
If you have a
large field, that's

00:45:31.960 --> 00:45:36.170
going to be the dominant
current source if you will.

00:45:36.170 --> 00:45:38.500
And when the electric
field is small,

00:45:38.500 --> 00:45:40.560
diffusion is going to dominate.

00:45:40.560 --> 00:45:43.380
So if we have a device
like this right here.

00:45:43.380 --> 00:45:46.380
And if I told you that the
built-in electric field was

00:45:46.380 --> 00:45:49.075
located pushed up toward
the top 1/100 of the device.

00:45:49.075 --> 00:45:51.830
So it was located very
close to the surface.

00:45:51.830 --> 00:45:55.230
You might surmise that
the drift current is going

00:45:55.230 --> 00:45:57.300
to be having a large influence.

00:45:57.300 --> 00:45:59.830
If you're a single
electron, you'll

00:45:59.830 --> 00:46:01.790
feel the influence
of the electric field

00:46:01.790 --> 00:46:03.440
near the front
surface of the device.

00:46:03.440 --> 00:46:06.480
And deep within the bulk,
the diffusion current

00:46:06.480 --> 00:46:11.830
is going to be driving the
carriers toward that junction.

00:46:11.830 --> 00:46:13.700
There's a relationship
between the mobility

00:46:13.700 --> 00:46:15.380
and the diffusivity of carriers.

00:46:15.380 --> 00:46:17.870
It's known as the
Einstein relation.

00:46:17.870 --> 00:46:19.390
And that's given
to you over there

00:46:19.390 --> 00:46:22.230
on the right-hand side
for a band conductor.

00:46:22.230 --> 00:46:24.610
Note that if you have--
this is an advanced concept.

00:46:24.610 --> 00:46:28.430
But if you have a dispersive
hopping mechanism,

00:46:28.430 --> 00:46:30.810
for instance, you may need
to become a little bit more

00:46:30.810 --> 00:46:33.310
sophisticated in how you relate
the diffusivity of a carrier

00:46:33.310 --> 00:46:34.180
to your mobility.

00:46:34.180 --> 00:46:36.970
But let's assume that is
valid for nice, well-behaved

00:46:36.970 --> 00:46:38.260
semiconductors.

00:46:38.260 --> 00:46:41.312
It's just a warning for those
who work on organic materials.

00:46:41.312 --> 00:46:44.040
I'd be happy to talk to you
more about that in a bit.

00:46:44.040 --> 00:46:46.756
So again, we have Gauss' law.

00:46:46.756 --> 00:46:48.630
The question is, what
is that electric field?

00:46:48.630 --> 00:46:49.540
What is arc psi?

00:46:49.540 --> 00:46:51.109
What is our built-in
electric field?

00:46:51.109 --> 00:46:52.650
Well, we know that
the charge density

00:46:52.650 --> 00:46:56.340
is going to be comprised
of the free hole

00:46:56.340 --> 00:46:59.940
density, the free electron
density, the fixed

00:46:59.940 --> 00:47:02.854
density of our donor atoms.

00:47:02.854 --> 00:47:04.645
You could think of
these as the phosphorus,

00:47:04.645 --> 00:47:07.890
the ionized phosphorus
atoms, and our fixed density

00:47:07.890 --> 00:47:09.650
of ionized acceptor atoms.

00:47:09.650 --> 00:47:12.455
We can also think of this as
our boron atoms and silicon.

00:47:12.455 --> 00:47:15.750
And so that is our fixed--
actually, not our fixed.

00:47:15.750 --> 00:47:16.760
These are fixed charges.

00:47:16.760 --> 00:47:17.610
These are mobile charges.

00:47:17.610 --> 00:47:19.900
But under equilibrium,
they've distributed themselves

00:47:19.900 --> 00:47:20.850
in a certain way.

00:47:20.850 --> 00:47:22.950
That is our charge
density, our rho.

00:47:22.950 --> 00:47:24.750
And that will figure
into Gauss' law

00:47:24.750 --> 00:47:27.300
and allow us to
calculate arc psi.

00:47:27.300 --> 00:47:32.390
And so in summa, we have here
arc psi as a function of dx.

00:47:32.390 --> 00:47:35.270
We have an expression that
relates the electric field

00:47:35.270 --> 00:47:38.725
to the density of dopant
atoms inside of our material.

00:47:38.725 --> 00:47:41.100
Note that we made one critical
assumption going from here

00:47:41.100 --> 00:47:44.690
to here, where we went from
the ionized donor and acceptor

00:47:44.690 --> 00:47:47.570
concentration to the total
dopant concentration.

00:47:47.570 --> 00:47:49.320
We're assuming that
everything is ionized.

00:47:49.320 --> 00:47:52.130
Again, because the
ionization energy,

00:47:52.130 --> 00:47:54.220
because the binding energy
of those free carriers

00:47:54.220 --> 00:47:57.190
to their dopant
atoms is so small

00:47:57.190 --> 00:48:01.400
that under kt, under thermal
energy at room temperature

00:48:01.400 --> 00:48:05.500
it's enough to
dissociate the charge.

00:48:05.500 --> 00:48:07.280
OK, so we've gotten to here.

00:48:07.280 --> 00:48:10.440
We can describe quantitatively
using this approximation,

00:48:10.440 --> 00:48:12.170
using the box function
approximation.

00:48:12.170 --> 00:48:14.870
We can describe the electric
field quantitatively.

00:48:14.870 --> 00:48:16.710
And now we have to
get to the potential

00:48:16.710 --> 00:48:19.530
and find the electron
energy as well.

00:48:19.530 --> 00:48:21.930
So we do a little
bit of accounting.

00:48:21.930 --> 00:48:24.500
If we want to account for
all of the electrons flowing

00:48:24.500 --> 00:48:26.750
through our system,
we would have

00:48:26.750 --> 00:48:30.430
to consider as well, in
any voxel of our material,

00:48:30.430 --> 00:48:32.580
in any unit volume
of our material,

00:48:32.580 --> 00:48:35.420
we have electrons going
in, electrons coming out.

00:48:35.420 --> 00:48:38.500
And within it, we could have
electrons being generated,

00:48:38.500 --> 00:48:41.270
say by light, or
electrons recombining.

00:48:41.270 --> 00:48:43.060
Meaning they're
losing their energy

00:48:43.060 --> 00:48:45.750
and falling back into a ground
state where they're bound.

00:48:45.750 --> 00:48:47.772
And that's this
U-term right here.

00:48:47.772 --> 00:48:49.730
And so the continuity
equations are essentially

00:48:49.730 --> 00:48:52.080
a set of accounting
equations that

00:48:52.080 --> 00:48:55.430
just describe the
difference, the net change,

00:48:55.430 --> 00:48:56.290
going in and out.

00:48:56.290 --> 00:48:58.460
If something changes
on either surface,

00:48:58.460 --> 00:49:01.110
it's because your either added
carriers or took them away.

00:49:01.110 --> 00:49:03.880
And the way you add is by
shining light on your sample

00:49:03.880 --> 00:49:05.120
and generating more carriers.

00:49:05.120 --> 00:49:06.480
G, for instance.

00:49:06.480 --> 00:49:09.590
That's one way of generating
carriers by adding light.

00:49:09.590 --> 00:49:11.020
Or recombination.

00:49:11.020 --> 00:49:13.606
And one way of recombining
is, for example,

00:49:13.606 --> 00:49:14.980
through a defect
in our material,

00:49:14.980 --> 00:49:17.070
where the electron
is moving along.

00:49:17.070 --> 00:49:19.844
It finds a defect and it falls
back into a ground state.

00:49:19.844 --> 00:49:22.260
So the continuity equations
are nothing more, nothing less

00:49:22.260 --> 00:49:24.310
than housekeeping, bookkeeping.

00:49:24.310 --> 00:49:26.630
But it's very important as
you'll see in the next slide

00:49:26.630 --> 00:49:29.670
right here where we
combine five equations that

00:49:29.670 --> 00:49:33.240
describe current transport
in a pn-junction.

00:49:33.240 --> 00:49:35.400
We have drift and
diffusion up here.

00:49:35.400 --> 00:49:37.120
Those are the
equations we just saw.

00:49:37.120 --> 00:49:39.520
We have the equation
describing the electric field.

00:49:39.520 --> 00:49:42.460
And we have our accounting
equations down here.

00:49:42.460 --> 00:49:45.010
And if we look at these
equations in unison,

00:49:45.010 --> 00:49:50.550
we'll notice that, oh, well, we
have our hole current appearing

00:49:50.550 --> 00:49:51.530
twice here.

00:49:51.530 --> 00:49:54.980
We have our electric field
appearing in two cases.

00:49:54.980 --> 00:49:55.530
Sorry.

00:49:55.530 --> 00:49:57.180
Back.

00:49:57.180 --> 00:49:58.620
Back.

00:49:58.620 --> 00:49:59.380
There.

00:49:59.380 --> 00:50:01.800
We have our electric field
appearing in those three

00:50:01.800 --> 00:50:03.070
equations right here.

00:50:03.070 --> 00:50:05.510
And we have a system
of non-linear equations

00:50:05.510 --> 00:50:10.200
as a result. It is not possible
to solve these analytically

00:50:10.200 --> 00:50:10.980
in their entirety.

00:50:10.980 --> 00:50:12.730
We'll have to make a
series of assumptions

00:50:12.730 --> 00:50:16.210
to really get to
the full solution.

00:50:16.210 --> 00:50:19.140
But it's possible to
solve them numerically

00:50:19.140 --> 00:50:21.520
using computer simulations.

00:50:21.520 --> 00:50:22.930
This is important
because we want

00:50:22.930 --> 00:50:25.540
to be able to define the current
coming out of our solar cell

00:50:25.540 --> 00:50:26.090
device.

00:50:26.090 --> 00:50:27.840
Without solving these
equations, we really

00:50:27.840 --> 00:50:30.130
don't understand what
the current is out

00:50:30.130 --> 00:50:33.110
of a pn-junction, out of a
solar cell under different bias

00:50:33.110 --> 00:50:33.670
conditions.

00:50:33.670 --> 00:50:35.836
That's why these equations
right here are important.

00:50:46.540 --> 00:50:49.260
What I want to do is not to
just dwell on the current.

00:50:49.260 --> 00:50:51.110
I want to emphasize
that to calculate

00:50:51.110 --> 00:50:53.230
the voltage across the
semiconductor-- sorry,

00:50:53.230 --> 00:50:56.910
a semiconductor device, a
pn-junction-based solar cell.

00:50:56.910 --> 00:50:59.670
To calculate the voltage
across a solar cell,

00:50:59.670 --> 00:51:02.660
we have to understand
a little bit more.

00:51:02.660 --> 00:51:07.810
So far, we've been assuming
that each electron is

00:51:07.810 --> 00:51:09.120
a unique individual.

00:51:09.120 --> 00:51:11.980
That an electron over here
is a small perturbation

00:51:11.980 --> 00:51:14.580
to a larger system in
that it will flow down

00:51:14.580 --> 00:51:16.440
based on that electric field.

00:51:16.440 --> 00:51:18.150
For a voltage,
we're really talking

00:51:18.150 --> 00:51:19.722
about an ensemble of electrons.

00:51:19.722 --> 00:51:21.180
All of the electrons
in the system.

00:51:21.180 --> 00:51:23.970
And so we have to define
some chemical potential

00:51:23.970 --> 00:51:24.920
for our system.

00:51:24.920 --> 00:51:27.510
We have to define
some-- one could

00:51:27.510 --> 00:51:30.090
think of it as an average
energy for our system.

00:51:30.090 --> 00:51:32.930
So let me define chemical
potential for you

00:51:32.930 --> 00:51:35.930
in a semiconductor.

00:51:35.930 --> 00:51:38.100
If we describe the
semiconductor-- here's

00:51:38.100 --> 00:51:40.110
our valence band and
our conduction band.

00:51:40.110 --> 00:51:43.270
This is our band gap right
here in between the two bands

00:51:43.270 --> 00:51:45.982
as described by e sub g, our
conduction band, valence band.

00:51:45.982 --> 00:51:47.940
And these little red dots
here are representing

00:51:47.940 --> 00:51:50.350
our covalently bonded
electrons in the ground

00:51:50.350 --> 00:51:53.260
state at 0 Kelvin.

00:51:53.260 --> 00:51:55.955
If we heat this material
up just a little bit,

00:51:55.955 --> 00:51:57.580
there will be some
fraction of carriers

00:51:57.580 --> 00:52:00.910
moving across into the
conduction band just

00:52:00.910 --> 00:52:02.680
through simple probability.

00:52:02.680 --> 00:52:06.330
And we'll get to the
precise equation that

00:52:06.330 --> 00:52:08.100
describes the
probability distribution

00:52:08.100 --> 00:52:10.020
function in a few lectures.

00:52:10.020 --> 00:52:12.440
But for now, let's just
assume that a certain number

00:52:12.440 --> 00:52:14.600
through thermal
processes are able to be

00:52:14.600 --> 00:52:16.580
excited across the band gap.

00:52:16.580 --> 00:52:18.920
So these are
thermally-excited electrons.

00:52:18.920 --> 00:52:22.270
And we call these-- this
is the intrinsic carrier

00:52:22.270 --> 00:52:23.270
concentration.

00:52:23.270 --> 00:52:25.420
So these carriers up here
are free to move around

00:52:25.420 --> 00:52:26.140
the crystal.

00:52:26.140 --> 00:52:27.400
They can conduct electricity.

00:52:27.400 --> 00:52:28.654
They can conduct charge.

00:52:28.654 --> 00:52:30.070
We could measure
a current flowing

00:52:30.070 --> 00:52:33.130
through if we applied a
bias voltage across material

00:52:33.130 --> 00:52:33.970
like this.

00:52:33.970 --> 00:52:35.230
Those are our charge carriers.

00:52:35.230 --> 00:52:36.500
These holes as well.

00:52:36.500 --> 00:52:40.516
And so this is the intrinsic
carrier concentration.

00:52:40.516 --> 00:52:41.890
To give you an
order of magnitude

00:52:41.890 --> 00:52:44.210
of the intrinsic carrier
concentration in silicon,

00:52:44.210 --> 00:52:48.290
it's around 10 to the 10
carriers per cubic centimeter.

00:52:48.290 --> 00:52:55.180
That's 1 over 10
to the 12 per atom.

00:52:55.180 --> 00:52:58.680
So each atom of silicon is
generating roughly 1 over 10

00:52:58.680 --> 00:53:01.080
to the 12 free carriers
due to this process.

00:53:01.080 --> 00:53:03.520
Very small concentration of
free carriers in the material.

00:53:03.520 --> 00:53:06.440
Around 5/10 into the 22
atoms per cubic centimeter

00:53:06.440 --> 00:53:09.660
and only 10 to the 10 free
carriers per cubic centimeter

00:53:09.660 --> 00:53:11.770
due to this thermal process
at room temperature.

00:53:11.770 --> 00:53:15.410
So it's a very small
effect in silicon.

00:53:15.410 --> 00:53:18.579
As you shrink your
band gap, the energy

00:53:18.579 --> 00:53:20.120
necessary to excite
across a band gap

00:53:20.120 --> 00:53:24.630
becomes less since you
have more thermal carriers.

00:53:24.630 --> 00:53:27.610
So the chemical potential is
describing the average energy

00:53:27.610 --> 00:53:30.950
necessary to remove an
infinitesimally small quantity

00:53:30.950 --> 00:53:33.200
of electrons to the system.

00:53:33.200 --> 00:53:35.640
And again, infinitesimally
small quantity meaning it's

00:53:35.640 --> 00:53:36.479
a mere perturbation.

00:53:36.479 --> 00:53:37.770
You're not changing the volume.

00:53:37.770 --> 00:53:39.680
You're not changing the
electrostatics of the system.

00:53:39.680 --> 00:53:41.630
You're just adding one
electron to the system,

00:53:41.630 --> 00:53:43.046
or taking it away,
and determining

00:53:43.046 --> 00:53:45.340
how much energy was required.

00:53:45.340 --> 00:53:48.030
And so we describe that
chemical potential,

00:53:48.030 --> 00:53:49.980
we call it by a different name.

00:53:49.980 --> 00:53:52.770
We call it Fermi level, but
it is the exact same thing.

00:53:52.770 --> 00:53:55.950
It's the energy necessary
to remove that electron

00:53:55.950 --> 00:53:57.930
from the material.

00:53:57.930 --> 00:53:59.740
So you can envision
that it's going

00:53:59.740 --> 00:54:03.320
to be the Fermi level on either
side of the pn-junction that

00:54:03.320 --> 00:54:05.480
will determine the voltage
output of our solar cell

00:54:05.480 --> 00:54:05.980
device.

00:54:05.980 --> 00:54:08.146
And that's why we want to
be able to calculate this.

00:54:10.420 --> 00:54:13.530
So let's look, first off what
happens to our Fermi level

00:54:13.530 --> 00:54:16.850
when we dope our material,
when we intentionally

00:54:16.850 --> 00:54:20.340
add, in this case, boron
atoms to make it p-type

00:54:20.340 --> 00:54:22.980
or phosphorus atoms to
make the material n-type.

00:54:22.980 --> 00:54:23.810
What happens?

00:54:23.810 --> 00:54:26.790
Well, we end up
shifting our Fermi level

00:54:26.790 --> 00:54:29.240
toward the valence band
or shifting the Fermi

00:54:29.240 --> 00:54:32.220
level toward the conduction
band by the addition of holes

00:54:32.220 --> 00:54:33.536
or electrons.

00:54:33.536 --> 00:54:35.410
An easy way to think
about it without getting

00:54:35.410 --> 00:54:38.120
into complicated semiconductor
math is the following.

00:54:38.120 --> 00:54:41.920
If I'm adding more electrons to
my system, by doping at n-type,

00:54:41.920 --> 00:54:44.507
essentially I'm shifting
the energy level up.

00:54:44.507 --> 00:54:45.965
It's an easy way
to think about it.

00:54:45.965 --> 00:54:47.880
If I'm removing the
electrons from the system

00:54:47.880 --> 00:54:50.710
by adding holes
down here, then I'm

00:54:50.710 --> 00:54:52.630
shifting the Fermi level down.

00:54:52.630 --> 00:54:53.830
Easy way to think about it.

00:54:53.830 --> 00:54:55.110
We'll get to the math.

00:54:55.110 --> 00:54:56.610
Actually, if you're
really curious,

00:54:56.610 --> 00:54:59.080
I think I included one
slide of the derivation

00:54:59.080 --> 00:55:00.880
of the precise
chemical potential

00:55:00.880 --> 00:55:03.850
so you can walk
through that as well.

00:55:03.850 --> 00:55:05.990
So voltage across a pn-junction.

00:55:05.990 --> 00:55:09.070
Under zero bias conditions,
this is in the dark

00:55:09.070 --> 00:55:10.820
and without a battery
pack attached to it.

00:55:10.820 --> 00:55:12.790
So this is an
unperturbed pn-junction

00:55:12.790 --> 00:55:19.090
just in the dark without
any external bias.

00:55:19.090 --> 00:55:23.130
We have the Fermi level
constant throughout.

00:55:23.130 --> 00:55:25.920
Both the p-type and
the n-type flat.

00:55:25.920 --> 00:55:28.780
Notice the bands are
bending, so the distance

00:55:28.780 --> 00:55:30.960
of the Fermi level
from the valence band

00:55:30.960 --> 00:55:33.640
here is smaller than the
distance from the Fermi level

00:55:33.640 --> 00:55:35.530
to the valence band in
the n-type material.

00:55:35.530 --> 00:55:36.690
That's because in
the n-type material

00:55:36.690 --> 00:55:38.064
we have more
electrons, and we're

00:55:38.064 --> 00:55:40.570
pushing the Fermi level higher.

00:55:40.570 --> 00:55:43.850
The vacuum level
follows these bands.

00:55:43.850 --> 00:55:45.722
It just happens to
be way up there.

00:55:45.722 --> 00:55:47.680
And so the amount of
energy necessary to remove

00:55:47.680 --> 00:55:50.480
the electron from the system,
to move it to the vacuum level,

00:55:50.480 --> 00:55:52.680
changes from the
p-type to the n-type.

00:55:52.680 --> 00:55:54.480
But for the purposes
of our diagram right

00:55:54.480 --> 00:55:58.140
here, we're drawing the Fermi
level constant throughout.

00:55:58.140 --> 00:56:02.030
Now, we have that transition
region, the depletion region,

00:56:02.030 --> 00:56:04.950
the space charge region--
all anonymous, same thing.

00:56:04.950 --> 00:56:08.100
We have that transition
region here in the middle.

00:56:08.100 --> 00:56:11.300
So if we begin quantifying
the different parameters here,

00:56:11.300 --> 00:56:15.350
we have a Fermi level distance
from the valence band.

00:56:15.350 --> 00:56:16.987
So that's this
distance right here.

00:56:16.987 --> 00:56:18.820
We have the distance
between the Fermi level

00:56:18.820 --> 00:56:21.130
and the conduction band
in the n-type material.

00:56:21.130 --> 00:56:24.040
And then we have our
built-in potential.

00:56:24.040 --> 00:56:27.220
And when we multiply our
built-in potential by q,

00:56:27.220 --> 00:56:28.085
we get an energy.

00:56:28.085 --> 00:56:32.600
Essentially, an energy gain
across that pn-junction.

00:56:32.600 --> 00:56:36.801
So that quantity here is equal
to the band gap minus these two

00:56:36.801 --> 00:56:37.300
parameters.

00:56:37.300 --> 00:56:40.230
Minus this, minus that.

00:56:40.230 --> 00:56:42.200
And so you can see that
the built-in potential

00:56:42.200 --> 00:56:45.392
across the junction is
benefited by higher doping.

00:56:45.392 --> 00:56:47.100
The higher we dope
our material, the more

00:56:47.100 --> 00:56:49.680
we shift our Fermi level
toward either band.

00:56:49.680 --> 00:56:52.630
And the greater the
separation we get,

00:56:52.630 --> 00:56:55.750
the smaller this quantity is,
the smaller that quantity is,

00:56:55.750 --> 00:56:57.900
and the more our built-in
potential approximates

00:56:57.900 --> 00:57:00.240
the actual band gap
of the material.

00:57:00.240 --> 00:57:02.524
This built-in potential
will relate to-- it

00:57:02.524 --> 00:57:03.940
wont' be identical
to, but it will

00:57:03.940 --> 00:57:06.760
be associated with
our maximum voltage

00:57:06.760 --> 00:57:08.737
that we can get
out of the device.

00:57:08.737 --> 00:57:11.070
And so we'll want to engineer
our material in such a way

00:57:11.070 --> 00:57:13.180
so as to maximize that quantity.

00:57:13.180 --> 00:57:15.750
That's important.

00:57:15.750 --> 00:57:20.010
The relation between our
built-in potential and the dope

00:57:20.010 --> 00:57:21.530
intensity is shown here.

00:57:21.530 --> 00:57:23.430
For now, you'll have
to take my word for it.

00:57:23.430 --> 00:57:26.170
I'm sparing you a lot of
semiconductor physics.

00:57:26.170 --> 00:57:28.170
It's written on the next
slide right here if you

00:57:28.170 --> 00:57:30.130
care to look in some detail.

00:57:30.130 --> 00:57:32.000
It's also described in,
I believe, Chapter 2

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:34.290
in Martin Green's textbook.

00:57:34.290 --> 00:57:37.015
But for now, let's assume that
the built-in junction potential

00:57:37.015 --> 00:57:39.170
is a function of the
dopant concentrations

00:57:39.170 --> 00:57:40.499
just by our intuition.

00:57:40.499 --> 00:57:42.290
If we're adding more
electrons to one side,

00:57:42.290 --> 00:57:45.960
we're going to be shifting
the Fermi energy up.

00:57:45.960 --> 00:57:49.760
OK, so the voltage
across a pn-junction.

00:57:49.760 --> 00:57:51.320
Now, let's bias our device.

00:57:51.320 --> 00:57:55.400
We have under zero bias
conditions this expression.

00:57:55.400 --> 00:57:57.550
Sorry, there we go.

00:57:57.550 --> 00:58:00.200
Under zero bias conditions,
we have that expression there.

00:58:00.200 --> 00:58:02.020
And under biased
conditions, now we

00:58:02.020 --> 00:58:04.700
have an applied biased
voltage, our V sub a.

00:58:04.700 --> 00:58:06.070
We're applying a bias voltage.

00:58:06.070 --> 00:58:08.130
We've effectively
shifted-- notice here,

00:58:08.130 --> 00:58:10.870
we've shifted our bands
when relative to the other.

00:58:10.870 --> 00:58:15.340
So we've shifted this side
up by a certain V sub a.

00:58:15.340 --> 00:58:20.510
And now if you'll notice
the quantities here,

00:58:20.510 --> 00:58:24.320
we have a separation
of the Fermi energy

00:58:24.320 --> 00:58:25.620
on one side to the other.

00:58:25.620 --> 00:58:28.610
There is a bias now
across this device.

00:58:28.610 --> 00:58:31.270
There is a driving
force for electrons

00:58:31.270 --> 00:58:34.230
to go and complete an
external circuit, to travel

00:58:34.230 --> 00:58:35.570
through the external circuit.

00:58:35.570 --> 00:58:37.028
Because the electrons
that are over

00:58:37.028 --> 00:58:40.390
here have a higher energy net
than the electrons over there--

00:58:40.390 --> 00:58:43.640
the ensemble, on average.

00:58:43.640 --> 00:58:47.529
The transition region,
likewise, will get smaller.

00:58:47.529 --> 00:58:48.570
Sorry for that animation.

00:58:48.570 --> 00:58:51.460
But if we keep track here,
the transition region

00:58:51.460 --> 00:58:53.800
becomes smaller
under forward bias.

00:58:53.800 --> 00:58:58.049
Because we're depleting-- we're
removing the amount of charge

00:58:58.049 --> 00:58:58.840
that was over here.

00:58:58.840 --> 00:59:00.130
We're squeezing it back.

00:59:00.130 --> 00:59:03.030
We're reducing that
barrier height.

00:59:03.030 --> 00:59:06.490
And so over here, if we
go back to this diagram,

00:59:06.490 --> 00:59:09.140
you can now draw in what's
written in these red circles.

00:59:09.140 --> 00:59:12.620
You can draw in the
actual depletion

00:59:12.620 --> 00:59:17.040
width, the width of the space
charge region on your diagrams,

00:59:17.040 --> 00:59:19.630
just like that.

00:59:19.630 --> 00:59:23.920
I'll give you just a second to
complete that diagram there.

00:59:23.920 --> 00:59:26.840
Under reverse bias, likewise,
the width of the depletion

00:59:26.840 --> 00:59:27.715
region will increase.

00:59:36.310 --> 00:59:38.390
And the depletion
region is increasing,

00:59:38.390 --> 00:59:39.950
the built-in charge
is increasing,

00:59:39.950 --> 00:59:41.815
the amount of band
bending is increasing,

00:59:41.815 --> 00:59:44.450
and the amount of drift
current also increasing.

00:59:44.450 --> 00:59:45.610
So it all fits together.

00:59:45.610 --> 00:59:48.490
It's beginning to really
come together nicely in one

00:59:48.490 --> 00:59:50.720
nice picture in our minds.

00:59:50.720 --> 00:59:55.028
So yes, one question.

