01:02:05.160 --> 01:02:09.930
So before we go into
detail into current flows,

01:02:09.930 --> 01:02:13.074
I wanted to touch on this
with the space charge region.

01:02:13.074 --> 01:02:15.240
We can describe the width
of the space charge region

01:02:15.240 --> 01:02:19.410
now by the built-in bias
across the junction.

01:02:19.410 --> 01:02:22.560
The applied bias right here
and some fundamental material

01:02:22.560 --> 01:02:24.400
properties as well.

01:02:24.400 --> 01:02:26.230
And this little
epsilon right here

01:02:26.230 --> 01:02:31.340
is essentially the dielectric
constant and the vacuum

01:02:31.340 --> 01:02:32.822
permittivity, a constant.

01:02:32.822 --> 01:02:34.530
And so you want to
take that into account

01:02:34.530 --> 01:02:36.610
when you're running your
actual calculations.

01:02:36.610 --> 01:02:39.540
It's very easy to be off on
the width of the space charge

01:02:39.540 --> 01:02:41.470
region by several
orders of magnitude

01:02:41.470 --> 01:02:46.060
if you don't do the proper
accounting for those fixed

01:02:46.060 --> 01:02:47.030
variables.

01:02:47.030 --> 01:02:49.110
And so if you walk
through the equations

01:02:49.110 --> 01:02:51.550
to describe the width of
the space charge region,

01:02:51.550 --> 01:02:54.140
you'll find that in a
typical solar cell device,

01:02:54.140 --> 01:02:55.422
it's on the order of a micron.

01:02:55.422 --> 01:02:57.630
And this is related to one
of your homework problems,

01:02:57.630 --> 01:03:00.230
so stash that away
somewhere in your brain.

01:03:00.230 --> 01:03:01.569
It's on the order of a micron.

01:03:01.569 --> 01:03:03.110
The width of that
space charge region

01:03:03.110 --> 01:03:05.380
typically could
be on that order.

01:03:05.380 --> 01:03:07.965
So it's going to
be some multiple.

01:03:07.965 --> 01:03:09.340
And the reason
that's interesting

01:03:09.340 --> 01:03:11.280
is because the entire
solar cell device

01:03:11.280 --> 01:03:14.110
is about 100 to 200 microns.

01:03:14.110 --> 01:03:17.590
That's for a crystalline
silicon device.

01:03:17.590 --> 01:03:20.590
That means that in a
crystalline silicon device,

01:03:20.590 --> 01:03:23.090
the diffusion current
is what's driving

01:03:23.090 --> 01:03:25.730
most of the current flow
inside of the solar cell.

01:03:25.730 --> 01:03:27.740
If our solar cell is
much, much, much thinner,

01:03:27.740 --> 01:03:30.470
say in the order of a micron,
then our drift current

01:03:30.470 --> 01:03:32.026
would be dominating.

01:03:32.026 --> 01:03:33.650
This is a more advanced
topic and we'll

01:03:33.650 --> 01:03:35.608
return to that when we
describe the differences

01:03:35.608 --> 01:03:38.400
between thin film operation and
crystalline silicon solar cell

01:03:38.400 --> 01:03:39.760
operation.

01:03:39.760 --> 01:03:41.060
Device capacitance.

01:03:41.060 --> 01:03:45.320
For those who are running
experimental measurements

01:03:45.320 --> 01:03:48.890
and want to determine
the RC time constant

01:03:48.890 --> 01:03:52.920
necessary to have the device
settle into a measurable state,

01:03:52.920 --> 01:03:54.480
that's there.

01:03:54.480 --> 01:03:57.060
And the capacitance
is described, again,

01:03:57.060 --> 01:04:00.500
by the various
properties as well as

01:04:00.500 --> 01:04:04.140
the built-in potential which is
related to the dopant density.

01:04:04.140 --> 01:04:07.810
OK, so under zero bias,
we have a concentration

01:04:07.810 --> 01:04:10.292
of holes on one side of
our junction that's high.

01:04:10.292 --> 01:04:12.750
In the p-type material, the
concentration of holes is high.

01:04:12.750 --> 01:04:15.690
And it's approximately equal
to the acceptor concentration.

01:04:15.690 --> 01:04:17.620
On the n-type side
of our junction,

01:04:17.620 --> 01:04:20.730
the whole population
is drastically reduced.

01:04:20.730 --> 01:04:25.480
And the flip side, our electron
concentration is very high

01:04:25.480 --> 01:04:27.877
and it drops into
the p-type side.

01:04:27.877 --> 01:04:29.710
So we have predominately
holes on this side.

01:04:29.710 --> 01:04:31.470
Predominately
electrons in that side.

01:04:31.470 --> 01:04:35.330
But a small concentration
of holes on the n-type side

01:04:35.330 --> 01:04:38.220
and a small concentration of
electrons in the p-type side.

01:04:38.220 --> 01:04:40.730
And we call this the
minority carrier.

01:04:40.730 --> 01:04:42.340
And we call that the
majority carrier.

01:04:42.340 --> 01:04:44.100
The majority carrier
is in the majority.

01:04:44.100 --> 01:04:46.220
The minority carrier
in the minority.

01:04:46.220 --> 01:04:48.890
And an interesting thing
happens when we bias our device.

01:04:48.890 --> 01:04:51.580
When we bias our
solar cell device,

01:04:51.580 --> 01:04:53.360
populations of both
carriers increase.

01:04:53.360 --> 01:04:56.070
But because this
is on a log scale,

01:04:56.070 --> 01:05:00.510
we're increasing this-- shall
we say the minority carrier

01:05:00.510 --> 01:05:04.610
concentration in an
absolute sense by a lot.

01:05:04.610 --> 01:05:08.240
And it's because of this drastic
uptick in the minority carrier

01:05:08.240 --> 01:05:11.060
concentration right at the
edge of the space charge region

01:05:11.060 --> 01:05:14.380
that we have current flow
across that junction.

01:05:14.380 --> 01:05:19.520
And that's described by a
series of equations here.

01:05:19.520 --> 01:05:22.420
Let's see, the way to walk
through the derivation,

01:05:22.420 --> 01:05:24.860
there's a series of
approximations to make.

01:05:24.860 --> 01:05:29.010
Think of it in terms of
electron and hole fluxes

01:05:29.010 --> 01:05:30.590
on either side of the junction.

01:05:30.590 --> 01:05:33.090
You can make a series of
assumptions as to what currents

01:05:33.090 --> 01:05:34.574
matter and which don't.

01:05:34.574 --> 01:05:36.240
You can, of course,
make the assumptions

01:05:36.240 --> 01:05:38.060
as to the charge
distribution as well,

01:05:38.060 --> 01:05:39.940
fixed using that box potential.

01:05:39.940 --> 01:05:44.830
And you can consider the cases
in which the minority carrier

01:05:44.830 --> 01:05:49.430
concentration here is dominating
to be the regions of interest

01:05:49.430 --> 01:05:52.380
for a current generation
inside of our device.

01:05:52.380 --> 01:05:56.500
And so if we walk through,
again the diffusion equation,

01:05:56.500 --> 01:05:59.360
the diffusion of carriers
at the edge of the space

01:05:59.360 --> 01:06:00.700
charge region.

01:06:00.700 --> 01:06:03.520
And from the
previous slides here,

01:06:03.520 --> 01:06:05.810
add our approximations
in, we will ultimately

01:06:05.810 --> 01:06:08.760
derive an expression that
has an exponential relation

01:06:08.760 --> 01:06:11.590
between current and our voltage.

01:06:11.590 --> 01:06:16.200
And if we continue through
the series of calculations,

01:06:16.200 --> 01:06:19.100
including the continuity
equation for accountability,

01:06:19.100 --> 01:06:20.950
we wind up with
an expression that

01:06:20.950 --> 01:06:23.670
looks like this right here,
where the total current flowing

01:06:23.670 --> 01:06:27.466
through the device will be
equal to the electron current

01:06:27.466 --> 01:06:29.340
at the edge of our space
charge region coming

01:06:29.340 --> 01:06:31.370
from the p-type side.

01:06:31.370 --> 01:06:34.000
The hole concentration
coming from the n-type side.

01:06:34.000 --> 01:06:35.660
The addition of
the two together.

01:06:35.660 --> 01:06:38.700
And that's effectively,
this equation right here,

01:06:38.700 --> 01:06:41.880
where we have an exponential
relation between current

01:06:41.880 --> 01:06:44.590
and voltage.

01:06:44.590 --> 01:06:50.610
So again, this we really
need to go home and study.

01:06:50.610 --> 01:06:52.894
And if you'd like to
do this pictorially,

01:06:52.894 --> 01:06:54.560
I provide you with
that link right there

01:06:54.560 --> 01:06:55.930
so you can see it visually.

01:06:55.930 --> 01:07:00.120
If you're more of a math type,
Chapters 3 and 4-- actually,

01:07:00.120 --> 01:07:03.580
Chapter 4 in Martin Green is
probably the best place to go.

01:07:03.580 --> 01:07:05.400
And the important
thing to keep in mind

01:07:05.400 --> 01:07:08.784
is that in the pn-junction,
the current flow

01:07:08.784 --> 01:07:10.200
across that junction
is determined

01:07:10.200 --> 01:07:13.830
by the minority carrier current
flow at the edge of the space

01:07:13.830 --> 01:07:15.380
charge region.

01:07:15.380 --> 01:07:18.460
And that's why we wind up
with the exponential relation

01:07:18.460 --> 01:07:21.060
between voltage and current.

01:07:21.060 --> 01:07:23.000
I decided the best
way to emphasize

01:07:23.000 --> 01:07:26.540
this voltage-current relation
is actually to measure it,

