01:14:28.530 --> 01:14:31.519
So the question was, when
you dope your material, what

01:14:31.519 --> 01:14:33.060
are the experimental
methods that you

01:14:33.060 --> 01:14:35.620
can use to really
determine whether or not

01:14:35.620 --> 01:14:40.110
the atoms have occupied a
substitutional position?

01:14:40.110 --> 01:14:43.930
One of the methods is called
Rutherford backscattering

01:14:43.930 --> 01:14:47.260
or channeling, IN channeling,
where you introduce ions

01:14:47.260 --> 01:14:48.320
down your lattice.

01:14:48.320 --> 01:14:50.360
And if there is an
atom here, for example,

01:14:50.360 --> 01:14:52.330
an interstitial
site, it will scatter

01:14:52.330 --> 01:14:54.680
some fraction of those
introduced ions back

01:14:54.680 --> 01:14:56.590
at the detector.

01:14:56.590 --> 01:15:01.460
And so channeling is one
characterization method

01:15:01.460 --> 01:15:06.310
for determining the interstitial
to substitutional ratio inside

01:15:06.310 --> 01:15:09.420
of a semiconducting material.

01:15:09.420 --> 01:15:13.350
Another way that we have
very strong evidence

01:15:13.350 --> 01:15:15.942
that boron is occupying a
substitutional site and not

01:15:15.942 --> 01:15:21.000
an interstitial site is we can
calculate the binding energy

01:15:21.000 --> 01:15:22.890
of this hole to
the boron atom here

01:15:22.890 --> 01:15:24.620
on the substitutional site.

01:15:24.620 --> 01:15:26.610
In principle, if the
interstitial was also--

01:15:26.610 --> 01:15:28.840
if it was a charge
to defect, we could

01:15:28.840 --> 01:15:33.190
calculate the binding energy
of the charge to that defect.

01:15:33.190 --> 01:15:35.840
And the density
functional theory

01:15:35.840 --> 01:15:37.770
could tell you which
is the more likely

01:15:37.770 --> 01:15:39.750
given your experimental
observation that you

01:15:39.750 --> 01:15:42.280
get about one hole for every
one boron anatomy inside

01:15:42.280 --> 01:15:43.359
of your sample.

01:15:43.359 --> 01:15:45.150
Boron has been studied
to death in silicon.

01:15:45.150 --> 01:15:47.150
It's pretty well-known
that it's substitutional.

01:15:47.150 --> 01:15:49.580
But if you're working with a
new semiconducting material,

01:15:49.580 --> 01:15:50.640
you never know.

01:15:50.640 --> 01:15:51.973
You have to run the experiments.

